1
00:01:01,591 --> 00:01:03,759
 Our story begins
high over New York City...

2
00:01:03,927 --> 00:01:05,511
in the luxurious
penthouse apartment...

3
00:01:05,679 --> 00:01:09,056
of perhaps
the most unlikely genius
the world has ever known.

4
00:01:10,684 --> 00:01:12,852
Oh. Sorry. You caught me
doing my yoga.

5
00:01:13,019 --> 00:01:14,019
You were expecting

6
00:01:14,104 --> 00:01:15,855
downward dog,
perhaps? 

7
00:01:16,940 --> 00:01:19,525
My name is Mr. Peabody.

8
00:01:19,693 --> 00:01:21,694
And since we're going to be
spending some time together...

9
00:01:21,862 --> 00:01:23,904
I'd like to tell you
a little bit about myself.

10
00:01:24,072 --> 00:01:25,239
You see,
ever since I was a pup...

11
00:01:25,407 --> 00:01:27,241
it was clear that
I was different.

12
00:01:29,286 --> 00:01:30,744
I tried
to fit in...

13
00:01:30,829 --> 00:01:31,871
No, thank you.

14
00:01:31,955 --> 00:01:33,581
...but never could.

15
00:01:34,124 --> 00:01:36,375
As I grew,
I saw more and more
of my littermates...

16
00:01:36,751 --> 00:01:39,420
being chosen by
their new families.

17
00:01:40,130 --> 00:01:43,048
But for some reason,
I never was.

18
00:01:45,260 --> 00:01:47,052
Come on, boy!
Fetch the stick!

19
00:01:47,554 --> 00:01:49,597
But why? Won't you
just throw it again?

20
00:01:49,764 --> 00:01:52,057
It's an exercise in futility.

21
00:01:52,225 --> 00:01:54,727
I don't want this one,
Mommy. He's sarcastic.

22
00:01:54,895 --> 00:01:56,896
Wait, wait!
Come back!
Throw the stick.

23
00:01:57,063 --> 00:01:59,773
I'll stay, I'll heel,
I'll even shake hands.

24
00:01:59,941 --> 00:02:01,484
Bark, bark?

25
00:02:01,651 --> 00:02:04,820
So, without
a family of my own...

26
00:02:04,988 --> 00:02:07,448
I dedicated myself to
the pursuit of knowledge...

27
00:02:07,741 --> 00:02:10,075
culture, and athletics.

28
00:02:11,912 --> 00:02:13,787
I received my
degree at Harvard.

29
00:02:13,955 --> 00:02:15,789
Vale-dog-torian, of course.

30
00:02:15,874 --> 00:02:16,916
 Yay!

31
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:19,919
And then,
I devoted myself
to helping mankind.

32
00:02:20,086 --> 00:02:22,755
I pioneered new techniques
in alternative energy.

33
00:02:24,925 --> 00:02:26,091
 Yay!

34
00:02:26,301 --> 00:02:28,761
Resolved
geopolitical conflicts
around the globe.

35
00:02:32,098 --> 00:02:33,182
And in my spare time...

36
00:02:33,266 --> 00:02:35,851
I invented
the fist bump, planking,
tearaway pants...

37
00:02:35,936 --> 00:02:37,019
Auto-Tune...

38
00:02:37,103 --> 00:02:38,312
the backside ollie...

39
00:02:38,396 --> 00:02:39,480
and Zumba.

40
00:02:39,564 --> 00:02:41,106
Now go

41
00:02:41,525 --> 00:02:42,691
Stop

42
00:02:43,193 --> 00:02:44,235
Drop

43
00:02:45,111 --> 00:02:46,237
Pause

44
00:02:46,863 --> 00:02:50,533
But what I'm most proud of
is my son, Sherman.

45
00:02:50,700 --> 00:02:52,785
Hi, Mr. Peabody.

46
00:02:52,869 --> 00:02:56,330
Oh! Have you
told them about the WABAC?

47
00:02:56,706 --> 00:02:58,791
 I was
just getting to that.

48
00:02:58,959 --> 00:03:02,294
When I adopted Sherman,
I vowed to be
the best father I could be.

49
00:03:02,462 --> 00:03:04,755
To prepare him for all
the wonders of the world,

50
00:03:04,839 --> 00:03:06,465
present and past.

51
00:03:06,633 --> 00:03:10,970
And so, Sherman
inspired the greatest
invention of my life...

52
00:03:11,555 --> 00:03:13,973
a time machine.

53
00:03:20,146 --> 00:03:23,899
Of course, time travel
can be a bit unpredictable.

54
00:03:24,067 --> 00:03:26,735
There are bound to be
a few mishaps along the way.

55
00:03:26,903 --> 00:03:28,320
Let's just say,
the Leaning Tower of Pisa

56
00:03:28,405 --> 00:03:30,239
wasn't always leaning.

57
00:03:30,407 --> 00:03:31,532
 But there's
nothing like learning

58
00:03:31,658 --> 00:03:32,783
the lessons of
history firsthand.

59
00:03:32,867 --> 00:03:33,909
Right, Sherman?

60
00:03:33,994 --> 00:03:35,869
Where are we going
today, Mr. Peabody?

61
00:03:36,037 --> 00:03:37,496
Not "where," Sherman.

62
00:03:37,664 --> 00:03:39,498
"When."

63
00:03:52,429 --> 00:03:55,431
 Whoa! This is
the biggest house
I've ever seen!

64
00:03:55,682 --> 00:03:58,559
 It's the Palace
of Versailles, home
of Marie Antoinette.

65
00:03:58,727 --> 00:04:01,186
You know,
she was mostly
famous for one thing.

66
00:04:01,354 --> 00:04:02,563
Cake!

67
00:04:02,731 --> 00:04:06,025
I love cake so much.

68
00:04:10,113 --> 00:04:12,906
Marie Antoinette
sure likes cake,
Mr. Peabody.

69
00:04:13,074 --> 00:04:14,199
 Oh!
Indeed she does.

70
00:04:14,367 --> 00:04:16,201
Marie was a woman
with a prodigious
appetite...

71
00:04:16,369 --> 00:04:18,370
for all things
covered with frosting.

72
00:04:18,538 --> 00:04:21,707
But her expensive tastes
made her the target
of much criticism.

73
00:04:21,875 --> 00:04:23,542
Why?
Because, Sherman...

74
00:04:23,710 --> 00:04:25,210
during Marie's reign,
the common people

75
00:04:25,378 --> 00:04:26,879
of France were
exceedingly poor.

76
00:04:27,881 --> 00:04:28,881
You've got any bread?

77
00:04:29,049 --> 00:04:31,884
No! I'm exceedingly poor.

78
00:04:32,469 --> 00:04:33,886
Now, can we
have some cake?

79
00:04:34,054 --> 00:04:35,054
Mais, oui.

80
00:04:35,221 --> 00:04:37,723
Oh, yeah, sorry.

81
00:04:37,891 --> 00:04:39,391
"May we" have some cake?

82
00:04:39,559 --> 00:04:40,726
Mais, oui!

83
00:04:41,227 --> 00:04:42,728
Maybe she can't hear me
through the hair.

84
00:04:42,896 --> 00:04:45,105
Sherman, what
the queen means is...

85
00:04:45,190 --> 00:04:48,192
Ah! 
Let them eat cake!

86
00:04:51,237 --> 00:04:54,406
When the queen
heard the poor of Paris
could not even buy bread...

87
00:04:54,574 --> 00:04:56,909
she said,
"Let them eat cake."

88
00:04:56,993 --> 00:04:57,868
No!

89
00:04:57,952 --> 00:04:59,161
I heard it myself.

90
00:04:59,287 --> 00:05:00,537
It's a scandal!
It's an outrage!

91
00:05:00,622 --> 00:05:01,747
Down with the queen!

92
00:05:01,831 --> 00:05:02,831
Down with the monarchy!

93
00:05:03,249 --> 00:05:04,291
Wait!

94
00:05:04,459 --> 00:05:06,085
What kind of cake?

95
00:05:13,510 --> 00:05:15,803
Smashing party,
Your Majesty.

96
00:05:16,179 --> 00:05:18,681
But now, I'm afraid
Sherman and I must be...

97
00:05:18,848 --> 00:05:21,100
Sherman? Sherman?

98
00:05:21,267 --> 00:05:22,976
Sherman!

99
00:05:24,938 --> 00:05:26,605
Sherman?

100
00:05:28,817 --> 00:05:31,443
Sherman! Here,
Sherman. 

101
00:05:31,986 --> 00:05:33,278
Hey, Mr. Peabody.

102
00:05:33,446 --> 00:05:35,155
What are you doing in here?

103
00:05:35,323 --> 00:05:36,532
Trying these other cakes.

104
00:05:36,700 --> 00:05:41,036
There's one in here
with whipped cream and
strawberries that's...

105
00:05:41,538 --> 00:05:42,705
pretty fantastic!

106
00:05:42,831 --> 00:05:43,956
Sherman...

107
00:05:44,124 --> 00:05:45,958
don't you remember
why I told you to stay

108
00:05:46,126 --> 00:05:47,960
close to me during
the French Revolution?

109
00:05:48,128 --> 00:05:49,837
Because after
the French Revolution...

110
00:05:50,004 --> 00:05:51,630
it was gonna rain?
Close.

111
00:05:51,798 --> 00:05:54,133
I said, "After the
French Revolution comes...

112
00:05:54,300 --> 00:05:56,427
the Reign of Terror!"

113
00:06:01,975 --> 00:06:04,810
Round up the aristocrats.

114
00:06:19,325 --> 00:06:22,244
The queen and her
aristocratic cronies...

115
00:06:22,412 --> 00:06:25,164
must pay the price
for their gluttony.

116
00:06:25,331 --> 00:06:28,250
We will slaughter them
like the dogs they are.

117
00:06:28,418 --> 00:06:30,335
Starting with this one!

118
00:06:30,837 --> 00:06:31,837
 Mr. Peabody!

119
00:06:32,672 --> 00:06:34,006
What should I do?

120
00:06:34,174 --> 00:06:37,009
Nothing, Sherman.
Just stay right there.

121
00:06:37,177 --> 00:06:38,343
But, Mr. Peabody!

122
00:06:38,511 --> 00:06:40,345
Everything is going
to be fine, Sherman.

123
00:06:40,513 --> 00:06:43,182
Just stay right there.

124
00:06:49,564 --> 00:06:51,398
Off with his head!

125
00:06:53,943 --> 00:06:56,487
Mr. Peabody!

126
00:07:02,035 --> 00:07:03,535
A cantaloupe?

127
00:07:03,703 --> 00:07:05,454
The lowest of the fruits.

128
00:07:05,622 --> 00:07:09,041
Who dares to insult me
with this melon?

129
00:07:12,921 --> 00:07:15,589
Get that dog!

130
00:07:16,216 --> 00:07:18,550
 Mr. Peabody,
how did you escape?

131
00:07:18,718 --> 00:07:19,843
It's simple, Sherman.

132
00:07:19,928 --> 00:07:21,637
I noticed the distance
between the sewer lids...

133
00:07:21,805 --> 00:07:23,055
reasoned that
there must be one

134
00:07:23,223 --> 00:07:24,431
directly under
the guillotine platform...

135
00:07:24,599 --> 00:07:26,058
noted the loose board
under the basket...

136
00:07:26,226 --> 00:07:27,267
computed the angle at
which the setting sun

137
00:07:27,393 --> 00:07:28,477
would bounce off
your glasses...

138
00:07:28,645 --> 00:07:30,437
momentarily blinding
the executioner...

139
00:07:30,605 --> 00:07:32,439
and chose that moment
to swipe
the executioner's melon...

140
00:07:32,607 --> 00:07:35,609
giving me the added weight
to tip the boards,
facilitating my exit.

141
00:07:35,777 --> 00:07:36,944
That's amazing!

142
00:07:37,111 --> 00:07:38,111
It's not amazing.

143
00:07:38,279 --> 00:07:40,572
It was just a matter
of keeping my head.

144
00:07:40,740 --> 00:07:42,491
"Keeping your head."

145
00:07:43,076 --> 00:07:44,159
I don't get it.

146
00:07:44,327 --> 00:07:46,578
There he is!
After them!

147
00:07:46,746 --> 00:07:48,413
Come, Sherman, quick!

148
00:07:52,085 --> 00:07:54,127
 Oh, this
water tastes terrible.

149
00:07:54,462 --> 00:07:56,088
Interestingly,
that's not water.

150
00:07:59,717 --> 00:08:01,301
Ha-ha!

151
00:08:01,761 --> 00:08:02,845
I've got you now.

152
00:08:05,306 --> 00:08:07,516
Indeed you have,
Monsieur Robespierre.

153
00:08:07,684 --> 00:08:10,477
And what a master
of the chase you are.

154
00:08:10,562 --> 00:08:11,687
Oh, you noticed?

155
00:08:11,771 --> 00:08:12,813
Of course.

156
00:08:12,897 --> 00:08:14,356
Doubling back on me
like that.

157
00:08:14,440 --> 00:08:15,524
That was genius.

158
00:08:15,692 --> 00:08:16,692
Thank you.

159
00:08:16,860 --> 00:08:18,777
I just hope you don't take
my little confederate, here.

160
00:08:18,945 --> 00:08:20,445
I depend on him
so completely.

161
00:08:20,613 --> 00:08:21,697
Get over here, you.

162
00:08:21,865 --> 00:08:23,448
Drats!
You're devilishly clever.

163
00:08:23,616 --> 00:08:25,993
I know.
And much quicker
than you as well.

164
00:08:26,160 --> 00:08:27,744
But are you quick
enough for this?

165
00:08:27,829 --> 00:08:29,121
Ha-ha! See? Quick!

166
00:08:29,455 --> 00:08:31,456
Quick, yes,
but not too smart.

167
00:08:31,541 --> 00:08:33,834
Oh! Another cantaloupe!

168
00:08:34,294 --> 00:08:35,294
Your sword!

169
00:08:35,795 --> 00:08:37,629
All right, Sherman,
looks like it's time

170
00:08:37,755 --> 00:08:39,506
for a little pop quiz
in the art of fencing.

171
00:08:39,674 --> 00:08:40,799
Go!

172
00:08:40,967 --> 00:08:43,343
Attack! Parry!
Thrust! Repeat!

173
00:08:43,511 --> 00:08:45,137
No.
Remise!

174
00:08:45,221 --> 00:08:46,513
 Good boy!

175
00:08:56,941 --> 00:08:58,483
Oh!

176
00:09:00,403 --> 00:09:01,904
Huh?

177
00:09:02,196 --> 00:09:03,488
Ha-ha! You missed!

178
00:09:03,656 --> 00:09:04,698
I never miss.

179
00:09:09,037 --> 00:09:10,913
 Hop on!

180
00:09:11,331 --> 00:09:12,831
 Whoa!

181
00:09:12,916 --> 00:09:15,083
Whoa! Whoa!

182
00:09:15,168 --> 00:09:18,045
Yeah! Whoa!

183
00:09:20,340 --> 00:09:21,590
Yeah!

184
00:09:21,758 --> 00:09:23,133
Do you smell that, Sherman?

185
00:09:23,259 --> 00:09:24,676
It wasn't me, Mr. Peabody.

186
00:09:24,761 --> 00:09:25,761
I know it wasn't you.

187
00:09:25,845 --> 00:09:27,512
It's the methane gas
in the sewer system.

188
00:09:27,680 --> 00:09:30,682
And given
the fact that it ignites
at 306 degrees Fahrenheit...

189
00:09:30,850 --> 00:09:31,850
we're about to use it...

190
00:09:32,018 --> 00:09:33,352
to blast out of here!

191
00:09:34,103 --> 00:09:35,687
Hang on!

192
00:09:41,361 --> 00:09:42,861
 Whoo!

193
00:09:45,949 --> 00:09:48,367
Wow!

194
00:09:55,541 --> 00:09:57,209
Nice landing, eh, Sherman?
Oof!

195
00:09:59,879 --> 00:10:01,755
So, what did you
learn today, Sherman?

196
00:10:01,923 --> 00:10:04,174
That French Revolution
was crazy.

197
00:10:04,258 --> 00:10:05,342
How so?

198
00:10:05,426 --> 00:10:07,636
All those guys
getting their
heads chopped off...

199
00:10:07,804 --> 00:10:10,389
and nobody standing up
and saying it wasn't right.

200
00:10:10,556 --> 00:10:13,058
And think, Marie Antoinette
could have avoided
the whole revolution...

201
00:10:13,226 --> 00:10:14,726
if she'd simply
issued an edict

202
00:10:14,852 --> 00:10:16,395
to distribute
bread amongst the poor.

203
00:10:16,562 --> 00:10:18,230
But then,
she couldn't have
had her dessert.

204
00:10:18,398 --> 00:10:19,731
Why not, Mr. Peabody?

205
00:10:19,899 --> 00:10:21,817
Because, Sherman,
you can't have

206
00:10:21,901 --> 00:10:24,277
your cake and edict, too.

207
00:10:26,072 --> 00:10:27,072
I don't get it.

208
00:10:37,583 --> 00:10:39,626
Where are we
gonna go tomorrow,
Mr. Peabody?

209
00:10:39,794 --> 00:10:42,796
Ancient Rome?
The Wild West? 1492?

210
00:10:42,964 --> 00:10:46,508
No, Sherman,
tomorrow we won't be going
to any of those places.

211
00:10:46,592 --> 00:10:47,718
Oh. Why not?

212
00:10:47,802 --> 00:10:48,927
Because
tomorrow's adventure...

213
00:10:49,095 --> 00:10:51,930
is one that you're
going to be taking
all on your own.

214
00:10:52,098 --> 00:10:53,473
What do you mean,
Mr. Peabody?

215
00:10:53,641 --> 00:10:54,641
Don't you remember?

216
00:10:54,809 --> 00:10:56,059
It's your first
day of school.

217
00:10:56,185 --> 00:10:58,311
Oh. Can I drive?
Of course not.

218
00:11:08,990 --> 00:11:12,617
PEABODY: Remember, Sherman,
"i" before "e,"
except after "c."

219
00:11:12,785 --> 00:11:14,453
I know, Mr. Peabody!

220
00:11:14,620 --> 00:11:16,538
And don't forget about
the commutative principle.

221
00:11:16,706 --> 00:11:18,206
Two plus three
equals three plus two.

222
00:11:18,374 --> 00:11:20,042
I know, Mr. Peabody!

223
00:11:20,209 --> 00:11:21,209
And if you have to
go to the bathroom...

224
00:11:21,377 --> 00:11:23,670
just raise your hand proudly
and say, "I have to go."

225
00:11:23,838 --> 00:11:25,505
I will, Mr. Peabody.

226
00:11:25,673 --> 00:11:28,383
And remember,
the No. 2 pencil is
standard for most uses...

227
00:11:28,551 --> 00:11:30,802
but there are times
when a No. 1 comes in handy.

228
00:11:30,970 --> 00:11:32,387
I left a little pencil chart
in your backpack...

229
00:11:32,555 --> 00:11:35,140
which you can consult
if it ever
becomes a judgment call.

230
00:11:35,308 --> 00:11:38,351
 I think
I'll be okay!

231
00:11:41,147 --> 00:11:42,147
Okay, bye, Mr. Peabody.

232
00:11:42,231 --> 00:11:43,273
 Wait.

233
00:11:43,357 --> 00:11:44,524
See you after school.
Sherman!

234
00:11:44,692 --> 00:11:47,652
I gotta go. I gotta
sign up for the clubs.

235
00:11:47,820 --> 00:11:49,571
No one is more in
favor of participation

236
00:11:49,697 --> 00:11:51,490
in fraternal
organizations than I.

237
00:11:51,657 --> 00:11:54,868
But before you go,
I want you to have this.

238
00:11:55,328 --> 00:11:56,870
Thanks. What is it?

239
00:11:57,038 --> 00:11:58,705
A dog whistle.

240
00:12:03,503 --> 00:12:06,004
It doesn't work,
Mr. Peabody.

241
00:12:06,172 --> 00:12:09,382
 It works
fine, Sherman.

242
00:12:09,550 --> 00:12:12,052
It's just a frequency
only dogs can hear.

243
00:12:12,678 --> 00:12:13,762
Oh, cool.

244
00:12:13,846 --> 00:12:16,389
Let that little keepsake
be a reminder to you...

245
00:12:16,557 --> 00:12:18,683
that no matter what
challenges you face,

246
00:12:18,851 --> 00:12:20,936
no matter how far
away I might seem...

247
00:12:21,104 --> 00:12:23,355
Bye, Mr. Peabody!

248
00:12:26,400 --> 00:12:28,777
...I'm with you.

249
00:12:36,244 --> 00:12:37,953
 George Washington.

250
00:12:39,080 --> 00:12:41,206
Who can tell me who he is?

251
00:12:41,374 --> 00:12:43,250
Oh, me! I can! I can!

252
00:12:43,334 --> 00:12:45,418
Uh... Sherman.

253
00:12:45,586 --> 00:12:48,380
The first president
of the United
States of America.

254
00:12:48,548 --> 00:12:49,714
 Good job.

255
00:12:49,882 --> 00:12:52,759
And when President Washington
was a little boy...

256
00:12:52,927 --> 00:12:55,762
what kind of tree
did he cut down?

257
00:12:55,930 --> 00:12:57,055
Ooh! Ooh, me! Me! Me!

258
00:12:57,223 --> 00:12:59,099
 Penny?
A cherry tree.

259
00:12:59,267 --> 00:13:00,350
Apocryphal.

260
00:13:00,476 --> 00:13:01,560
What kind of
tree is that?

261
00:13:01,727 --> 00:13:03,979
It's not a tree.
It's a word.
"Apocryphal."

262
00:13:04,147 --> 00:13:05,814
It means that
story is not true.

263
00:13:05,982 --> 00:13:07,566
Really?
Yeah.

264
00:13:07,733 --> 00:13:09,651
George Washington
never cut down
a cherry tree...

265
00:13:09,819 --> 00:13:11,403
and he never said
he couldn't lie.

266
00:13:11,571 --> 00:13:14,406
People made those
stories up to teach kids
a lesson about lying...

267
00:13:14,574 --> 00:13:15,532
but they're not true.

268
00:13:15,616 --> 00:13:16,867
He did cross
the Delaware River,

269
00:13:16,951 --> 00:13:19,578
Christmas night,
1776, though.

270
00:13:19,912 --> 00:13:22,164
My dad took me
there this summer.
We crossed it, too.

271
00:13:22,331 --> 00:13:24,332
I fell in.

272
00:13:25,501 --> 00:13:29,629
Looks like someone
really knows their
history, huh, Penny?

273
00:13:36,095 --> 00:13:37,470
 It's really great
meeting you guys.

274
00:13:37,597 --> 00:13:39,514
Maybe you can come over
to my house sometime.

275
00:13:39,682 --> 00:13:42,475
I could bring my new model.
It's a hydrogen atom.

276
00:13:42,643 --> 00:13:44,269
You've only got one, huh?

277
00:13:44,437 --> 00:13:46,229
Guess we'll
have to split it.

278
00:13:47,481 --> 00:13:48,481
 Good one!

279
00:13:50,526 --> 00:13:51,943
Check it, guys.

280
00:13:54,280 --> 00:13:56,198
What do you got there,
Sherman?

281
00:13:56,365 --> 00:13:57,657
Kibbles or bits?

282
00:13:57,825 --> 00:13:59,993
Actually,
I've got baby carrots,

283
00:14:00,119 --> 00:14:02,287
organic apple juice,
and a tuna sandwich.

284
00:14:03,331 --> 00:14:05,874
It's super-high
in omega-3s.

285
00:14:06,042 --> 00:14:08,627
So, you eat
human food, huh?

286
00:14:08,794 --> 00:14:10,295
Yeah. Why wouldn't I?

287
00:14:10,463 --> 00:14:11,546
Because you're a dog.

288
00:14:11,714 --> 00:14:12,797
No, I'm not.

289
00:14:12,965 --> 00:14:16,134
Sure you are.
Your dad is a dog,
so you're a dog, too.

290
00:14:16,302 --> 00:14:18,637
I think you're confused.
It's an adoptive
relationship.

291
00:14:18,804 --> 00:14:20,305
Zip it, Carl.
Okay.

292
00:14:20,473 --> 00:14:22,641
Here, I'll show you.
Fetch!

293
00:14:25,144 --> 00:14:27,229
Go on, doggy.
Go get your lunch.

294
00:14:27,313 --> 00:14:28,313
Go on.

295
00:14:28,397 --> 00:14:29,397
Go get it.

296
00:14:31,067 --> 00:14:33,151
Ugh. The humiliation.

297
00:14:33,319 --> 00:14:35,987
 Sherman,
go get your food.

298
00:14:36,155 --> 00:14:38,031
Make like
a good little doggy.

299
00:14:45,665 --> 00:14:47,374
What's this?
It's mine!

300
00:14:47,541 --> 00:14:49,000
Give it back!

301
00:14:49,126 --> 00:14:51,169
What is it? A whistle?

302
00:14:52,338 --> 00:14:54,464
Ugh! Stupid thing
doesn't even work.

303
00:14:54,590 --> 00:14:56,091
It's a dog
whistle, Penny.

304
00:14:56,259 --> 00:14:58,677
It operates at a frequency
that only dogs can hear.

305
00:14:58,844 --> 00:15:00,428
Back up, Carl.
Okay.

306
00:15:00,596 --> 00:15:02,889
Penny, that whistle
is my private property.

307
00:15:03,057 --> 00:15:05,016
Give it back!
Jump, doggy,
jump. 

308
00:15:05,184 --> 00:15:06,351
I am not a dog.

309
00:15:06,519 --> 00:15:07,519
Come on, Sherman!

310
00:15:07,687 --> 00:15:10,355
Just admit it.
You're a dog. Say it.

311
00:15:10,523 --> 00:15:11,564
 Let me go!

312
00:15:11,732 --> 00:15:14,192
Not until you beg like a dog.

313
00:15:14,360 --> 00:15:16,111
Come on, Sherman. Beg!

314
00:15:16,279 --> 00:15:18,863
Fight, fight, fight!

315
00:15:20,533 --> 00:15:24,369
Mr. Peabody,
thank you for coming in
on such short notice...

316
00:15:24,537 --> 00:15:26,705
to discuss
the problem with Sherman.

317
00:15:26,872 --> 00:15:28,707
Oh, it's not a problem
at all, Principal Purdy.

318
00:15:28,874 --> 00:15:30,041
I fully expected this.

319
00:15:30,209 --> 00:15:31,209
You did?
Yes.

320
00:15:31,377 --> 00:15:33,670
And, as with all
things Sherman-related,
I prepared for it.

321
00:15:33,838 --> 00:15:35,171
Here's a curriculum
that takes Sherman's

322
00:15:35,298 --> 00:15:36,673
advanced preparation
into account...

323
00:15:36,841 --> 00:15:38,508
but won't require you
to have him skip
one or more grades.

324
00:15:38,592 --> 00:15:39,592
Mr. Peabody...

325
00:15:39,677 --> 00:15:42,053
Here are some
pre-algebra worksheets,
an advanced reading list...

326
00:15:42,221 --> 00:15:43,972
and a link to
a website I created

327
00:15:44,098 --> 00:15:45,849
so he can start
studying Mandarin Chinese.

328
00:15:46,017 --> 00:15:47,559
It is, after all,
the language of the future.

329
00:15:47,727 --> 00:15:48,727
Mr. Peabody!

330
00:15:48,811 --> 00:15:50,812
I'm not saying he
shouldn't study French,
too, Principal Purdy.

331
00:15:50,980 --> 00:15:52,063
I'm saying
have him do both.

332
00:15:52,231 --> 00:15:53,231
Mr. Peabody!

333
00:15:53,399 --> 00:15:55,066
What? Not enough? Swahili?

334
00:15:57,069 --> 00:15:58,820
Sherman got
into a fight today.

335
00:15:59,530 --> 00:16:00,739
Oh, dear.

336
00:16:01,574 --> 00:16:02,907
Pictures were taken...

337
00:16:03,075 --> 00:16:05,243
for insurance purposes.

338
00:16:12,585 --> 00:16:14,336
 He bit her.

339
00:16:15,212 --> 00:16:19,591
I must say,
it doesn't look good
for you, Mr. Peabody.

340
00:16:19,759 --> 00:16:22,844
After all, you are a dog.

341
00:16:23,012 --> 00:16:24,846
Who, may I ask, are you?

342
00:16:25,014 --> 00:16:28,516
I am Ms. Grunion from
the Bureau of Child
Safety and Protection.

343
00:16:28,684 --> 00:16:32,437
We're required by
law to contact them
whenever there's an...

344
00:16:33,439 --> 00:16:34,439
incident.

345
00:16:35,107 --> 00:16:37,609
Sherman has never done
anything like this before.

346
00:16:37,777 --> 00:16:39,277
I'm sure he must
have had a reason.

347
00:16:39,445 --> 00:16:41,237
Well, the girl was being
a bit of a bully...

348
00:16:41,405 --> 00:16:42,614
 Quiet, Purdy!

349
00:16:42,782 --> 00:16:45,033
It's normal for
children to tease.

350
00:16:45,201 --> 00:16:47,702
It's not normal
for them to bite.

351
00:16:47,870 --> 00:16:50,538
Clearly, it's because of
how he's being raised.

352
00:16:50,706 --> 00:16:53,375
In my opinion,
a dog can never be

353
00:16:53,501 --> 00:16:56,211
a suitable parent
to a little boy.

354
00:16:56,379 --> 00:16:57,629
I must point out,
Ms. Grunion...

355
00:16:57,797 --> 00:16:59,547
that I won
the right to adopt Sherman

356
00:16:59,632 --> 00:17:00,799
in a court of law.

357
00:17:00,966 --> 00:17:03,718
And the court can
take it away from you.

358
00:17:04,470 --> 00:17:08,306
I'll be coming to your
home tomorrow evening
to conduct an investigation.

359
00:17:08,474 --> 00:17:12,102
If I discover that
you are, in any way,
an unfit parent...

360
00:17:12,269 --> 00:17:15,980
I will see to it
Sherman is removed
from your custody.

361
00:17:21,278 --> 00:17:22,779
Permanently.

362
00:17:23,322 --> 00:17:26,616
I hope I've made
myself clear.

363
00:17:30,246 --> 00:17:31,413
Crystal.

364
00:17:33,499 --> 00:17:36,126
 I'm sorry
I bit her, Mr. Peabody.

365
00:17:36,293 --> 00:17:37,669
I won't do it again.

366
00:17:37,837 --> 00:17:39,295
You're darn tooting
you won't do it again.

367
00:17:39,463 --> 00:17:42,340
This kind of wanton violence
is totally unacceptable.

368
00:17:42,508 --> 00:17:45,760
And rather uncharacteristic,
given how you feel
about Mr. Gandhi.

369
00:17:46,470 --> 00:17:48,304
What on earth provoked it?

370
00:17:51,976 --> 00:17:54,644
 She called me
a dog.

371
00:18:01,861 --> 00:18:04,154
Well, all right then.

372
00:18:06,282 --> 00:18:07,949
Thank you for telling me.

373
00:18:09,034 --> 00:18:10,869
Try and get some sleep.

374
00:18:15,040 --> 00:18:17,500
I love you, Mr. Peabody.

375
00:18:18,878 --> 00:18:21,838
I have a deep regard
for you as well, Sherman.

376
00:18:47,740 --> 00:18:49,282
Close your eyes

377
00:18:52,328 --> 00:18:54,204
Have no fear

378
00:18:56,123 --> 00:18:59,918
The master's gone
He's on the run

379
00:19:00,002 --> 00:19:02,337
And your daddy's here

380
00:19:05,049 --> 00:19:08,843
Beautiful, beautiful,
beautiful, beautiful boy

381
00:19:26,070 --> 00:19:27,946
Say a little prayer

382
00:19:30,950 --> 00:19:34,452
Every day,
in every way

383
00:19:34,578 --> 00:19:37,372
It's getting
better and better

384
00:19:39,542 --> 00:19:44,754
Beautiful, beautiful,
beautiful, beautiful boy

385
00:19:48,676 --> 00:19:53,471
Beautiful, beautiful,
beautiful, beautiful boy

386
00:19:57,226 --> 00:19:59,561
A hard road to hoe

387
00:20:00,187 --> 00:20:03,606
Yes, it's a long way to go

388
00:20:04,066 --> 00:20:06,776
But in the meantime

389
00:20:13,867 --> 00:20:15,994
Take my hand

390
00:20:19,915 --> 00:20:24,002
Life is what happens
to you while you're busy
making other plans

391
00:20:26,714 --> 00:20:32,176
Beautiful, beautiful,
beautiful, beautiful boy

392
00:20:36,599 --> 00:20:40,685
Beautiful, beautiful,
beautiful, beautiful boy

393
00:20:43,147 --> 00:20:44,272
Mr. Peabody...

394
00:20:44,440 --> 00:20:46,482
you are
a Nobel Prize-winning
scientist.

395
00:20:46,650 --> 00:20:48,192
An advisor to
heads of state.

396
00:20:48,360 --> 00:20:50,111
A captain of industry.

397
00:20:50,279 --> 00:20:52,780
Why would you
want to adopt a boy?

398
00:20:52,948 --> 00:20:54,449
Because, Your Honor...

399
00:20:54,617 --> 00:21:00,204
when I found Sherman,
it reminded me of how
I started out in life.

400
00:21:00,372 --> 00:21:04,208
And now, I want to give him
the one thing I always wanted.

401
00:21:04,376 --> 00:21:05,627
A home.

402
00:21:05,794 --> 00:21:08,379
And you're sure you're
capable of meeting
all the challenges...

403
00:21:08,547 --> 00:21:10,340
of raising a human boy?

404
00:21:10,549 --> 00:21:13,718
With all due respect,
how hard could it be?

405
00:21:15,721 --> 00:21:16,888
Very well, then.

406
00:21:17,056 --> 00:21:19,057
If a boy can adopt a dog...

407
00:21:19,224 --> 00:21:22,894
I see no reason
why a dog cannot adopt a boy.

408
00:21:27,066 --> 00:21:28,566
Da-da!

409
00:21:28,734 --> 00:21:30,193
No, Sherman, not "Da-da."

410
00:21:30,361 --> 00:21:32,570
You shall call me
"Mr. Peabody."

411
00:21:32,738 --> 00:21:35,406
Or, in less formal moments,
simply "Peabody."

412
00:21:36,909 --> 00:21:38,076
That's right.

413
00:21:38,410 --> 00:21:39,911
"Mr. Pea-baba."

414
00:21:40,663 --> 00:21:45,291
Beautiful, beautiful,
beautiful, beautiful boy

415
00:22:22,454 --> 00:22:23,538
What's cooking, Mr. Peabody?

416
00:22:23,664 --> 00:22:24,789
Oh, nothing much.

417
00:22:24,957 --> 00:22:28,126
Just a little Dungeness
crab with a passion-fruit
basil concassé.

418
00:22:28,293 --> 00:22:30,253
Some truffled quails
in a juniper-berry reduction.

419
00:22:30,421 --> 00:22:32,255
And Baked Alaska.

420
00:22:32,423 --> 00:22:35,049
Wow! Is today some
kind of special occasion?

421
00:22:35,134 --> 00:22:36,134
You could say.

422
00:22:36,218 --> 00:22:37,510
It's not my birthday.

423
00:22:37,636 --> 00:22:38,928
No, it isn't.

424
00:22:39,096 --> 00:22:40,179
It's not your birthday.

425
00:22:40,305 --> 00:22:41,472
Right again.

426
00:22:41,640 --> 00:22:43,641
It's not Father's Day.
Is it?

427
00:22:43,809 --> 00:22:46,144
Nope. It's not Father's Day.

428
00:22:46,770 --> 00:22:48,604
Is the president
coming to dinner again?

429
00:22:48,772 --> 00:22:50,565
No.
Oh.

430
00:22:50,941 --> 00:22:52,275
So, who's coming
to dinner?

431
00:22:52,443 --> 00:22:54,819
Let's just say,
if the evening
is a success...

432
00:22:54,987 --> 00:22:57,655
we can put this whole
"biting" business behind us.

433
00:23:04,747 --> 00:23:07,415
The Petersons! Welcome.

434
00:23:07,583 --> 00:23:08,666
So, he's
literally a dog.

435
00:23:08,834 --> 00:23:09,917
Paul!

436
00:23:10,085 --> 00:23:11,085
No, that's all right.

437
00:23:11,253 --> 00:23:13,963
Although,
I prefer "literate dog."

438
00:23:14,047 --> 00:23:15,256
 That's funny.

439
00:23:15,340 --> 00:23:16,674
Isn't that funny, Paul?

440
00:23:17,968 --> 00:23:19,886
 He's not
a big laugher.

441
00:23:20,429 --> 00:23:22,638
We're so delighted
you could make it
on such short notice.

442
00:23:22,806 --> 00:23:26,851
Aren't we, Sherman?

443
00:23:27,019 --> 00:23:30,354
Yeah, we're interested
in what's going on,
that's for sure.

444
00:23:30,522 --> 00:23:32,356
Say hello to
Penny, Sherman.

445
00:23:32,524 --> 00:23:33,983
Hi, Penny.

446
00:23:34,276 --> 00:23:35,651
Hello, Sherman.

447
00:23:35,819 --> 00:23:37,361
Now, why don't
you go show Penny

448
00:23:37,529 --> 00:23:39,113
your mineral collection,
Sherman?

449
00:23:39,281 --> 00:23:40,823
I'm sure she'll find
those new geodes

450
00:23:40,908 --> 00:23:42,533
of yours fascinating.

451
00:23:43,285 --> 00:23:44,619
Come on.

452
00:23:47,039 --> 00:23:49,707
I am so glad you
accepted my invitation.

453
00:23:49,875 --> 00:23:53,211
Now, the kids can
resolve their differences
before Ms. Grunion arrives.

454
00:23:53,378 --> 00:23:55,630
You're barking up
the wrong tree, mister.
In fact...

455
00:23:55,798 --> 00:23:58,049
if it weren't for Patty,
I would have pressed
charges already.

456
00:23:58,217 --> 00:23:59,509
And I have to
tell you, Peabody...

457
00:23:59,676 --> 00:24:01,135
where my daughter
is concerned,

458
00:24:01,261 --> 00:24:02,720
nothing is more
important than...

459
00:24:02,888 --> 00:24:05,348
Hello. Sure,
I'll take a survey.

460
00:24:14,358 --> 00:24:15,983
Everything going
swimmingly?

461
00:24:16,068 --> 00:24:17,235
Ugh.

462
00:24:17,569 --> 00:24:19,987
Why didn't you tell me
she was coming over here?

463
00:24:20,155 --> 00:24:22,240
Because I didn't
want you to worry.

464
00:24:22,407 --> 00:24:24,575
Okay, because I
didn't want to listen
to your bellyaching.

465
00:24:24,743 --> 00:24:27,203
Thank you for your honesty.

466
00:24:27,371 --> 00:24:28,329
You're welcome.

467
00:24:28,413 --> 00:24:31,082
I don't know what you
think we're supposed to
do in here anyway.

468
00:24:31,250 --> 00:24:32,667
She hates me.

469
00:24:32,835 --> 00:24:34,877
Share your interests.
Tell a witty anecdote.

470
00:24:35,045 --> 00:24:36,087
Mr. Peabody...

471
00:24:36,255 --> 00:24:37,672
I hate her.

472
00:24:37,840 --> 00:24:39,715
Sherman,
every great relationship...

473
00:24:39,883 --> 00:24:41,259
starts from
a place of conflict,

474
00:24:41,385 --> 00:24:42,760
and evolves into
something richer.

475
00:24:44,513 --> 00:24:45,847
Bonne chance.

476
00:24:47,057 --> 00:24:48,349
Make it work.

477
00:24:49,017 --> 00:24:50,601
But don't tell her
about the WABAC.

478
00:24:54,356 --> 00:24:57,441
 Don't even
think about it.

479
00:24:57,943 --> 00:24:59,443
Ah.

480
00:25:11,623 --> 00:25:13,541
 Peabody,
that was amazing!

481
00:25:13,792 --> 00:25:15,626
Paul, wasn't that amazing?

482
00:25:15,794 --> 00:25:17,086
I'm more into
rock-'n'-roll.

483
00:25:23,093 --> 00:25:24,468
I meant flamenco.

484
00:25:31,435 --> 00:25:32,435
Bagpipes?

485
00:25:33,437 --> 00:25:34,729
Uh, didgeridoo.

486
00:25:38,317 --> 00:25:39,317
Sitar.

487
00:25:39,610 --> 00:25:40,776
Steel drums.

488
00:25:40,944 --> 00:25:41,986
Trombone.

489
00:25:42,154 --> 00:25:43,446
Xylophone.

490
00:25:43,614 --> 00:25:44,614
Djembe?

491
00:25:44,781 --> 00:25:45,823
Calliope.

492
00:25:45,991 --> 00:25:47,450
Oboe. Piccolo.

493
00:25:47,618 --> 00:25:49,076
Tuba. Dobro.

494
00:25:49,244 --> 00:25:50,411
Slide whistle. Yodeling.

495
00:25:50,579 --> 00:25:51,621
Hurdy-gurdy. Ocarina.

496
00:25:51,788 --> 00:25:52,997
Harmonium. Musical saw.

497
00:25:53,165 --> 00:25:54,999
You know what?
This has been great...

498
00:25:55,167 --> 00:25:57,251
but a complete
waste of time.

499
00:25:57,419 --> 00:26:00,004
Now, let's get Penny
and go home!

500
00:26:00,172 --> 00:26:01,255
Are you all right, Paul?

501
00:26:01,340 --> 00:26:03,966
I'm... fine.

502
00:26:04,134 --> 00:26:05,593
 This happens
whenever he's tense.

503
00:26:05,761 --> 00:26:06,761
Paul, if I might...

504
00:26:06,845 --> 00:26:07,970
Stay away
from me, Peabody!

505
00:26:08,138 --> 00:26:10,514
Just get back!
I need traction.

506
00:26:10,682 --> 00:26:13,768
You can trust me, Paul.
I'm a licensed chiropractor.

507
00:26:13,852 --> 00:26:15,269
Ow! Huh.

508
00:26:23,195 --> 00:26:25,446
Ooh...

509
00:26:26,448 --> 00:26:27,949
Ah...

510
00:26:28,367 --> 00:26:29,700
Peabody...

511
00:26:29,868 --> 00:26:31,160
I feel great.

512
00:26:31,244 --> 00:26:33,955
I... 
I really feel great!

513
00:26:34,206 --> 00:26:36,457
 Peabody,
you're a miracle worker.

514
00:26:37,709 --> 00:26:39,710
Ha-ha! Look at me!

515
00:26:39,836 --> 00:26:41,379
I'm dancing!

516
00:26:43,548 --> 00:26:44,632
You know, Penny...

