00:26:44,716 --> 00:26:47,176
Sigmund Freud says
if you don't like a person...

518
00:26:47,344 --> 00:26:51,013
it's because they remind
you of something you
don't like about yourself.

519
00:26:51,181 --> 00:26:52,974
What do you know
about Sigmund Freud?

520
00:26:53,141 --> 00:26:54,225
More than you think.

521
00:26:54,393 --> 00:26:56,852
Sure.
Just like you know
all that stuff...

522
00:26:57,020 --> 00:27:00,564
about George Washington
not really cutting
down the cherry tree.

523
00:27:00,732 --> 00:27:01,899
Ugh. What a crock.

524
00:27:02,067 --> 00:27:03,067
But it's true!

525
00:27:03,235 --> 00:27:04,860
How do you know?
I just know!

526
00:27:05,028 --> 00:27:06,404
Did you read it in a book?
No!

527
00:27:06,571 --> 00:27:07,697
See it in a movie?
No!

528
00:27:07,864 --> 00:27:08,864
Did your brainiac
dad tell you?

529
00:27:08,991 --> 00:27:09,991
No!

530
00:27:10,158 --> 00:27:11,200
So, how do
you know, Sherman?

531
00:27:11,368 --> 00:27:12,660
How do you know?

532
00:27:12,744 --> 00:27:13,911
He told me.

533
00:27:13,996 --> 00:27:15,037
Who told you?

534
00:27:15,122 --> 00:27:16,664
George Washington.

535
00:27:18,417 --> 00:27:19,834
George Washington?

536
00:27:21,253 --> 00:27:22,503
Yeah.

537
00:27:22,921 --> 00:27:24,088
Ugh! Liar.

538
00:27:27,592 --> 00:27:29,427
But don't tell
her about the WABAC.

539
00:27:30,595 --> 00:27:32,179
He calls it the "WABAC."

540
00:27:32,347 --> 00:27:34,098
So, where have
you gone in it?

541
00:27:34,266 --> 00:27:36,726
Not "where," Penny, "when."

542
00:27:36,893 --> 00:27:39,395
Okay, smart guy, when?

543
00:27:39,563 --> 00:27:44,233
Oh, 1965, 1776, 1620...

544
00:27:44,401 --> 00:27:48,112
1492, 1215, 4.

545
00:27:48,280 --> 00:27:50,239
Can it go back to an hour ago?
Why?

546
00:27:50,407 --> 00:27:52,742
Because I could take it home,
pretend to be sick...

547
00:27:52,909 --> 00:27:54,785
and not come to
this lame dinner party.

548
00:27:54,870 --> 00:27:57,830
Ha-ha. Mr. Peabody says
you should never
use the WABAC...

549
00:27:58,081 --> 00:28:00,124
to travel to
a time when you existed.

550
00:28:00,292 --> 00:28:01,333
How come?

551
00:28:01,418 --> 00:28:02,376
There would be two of you.

552
00:28:02,461 --> 00:28:04,295
Oh, yeah.

553
00:28:04,463 --> 00:28:06,213
I guess the world's
not ready for that.

554
00:28:09,968 --> 00:28:11,385
Wow.

555
00:28:12,304 --> 00:28:15,347
Um, well, now that
we've seen it, maybe
we should go back.

556
00:28:15,599 --> 00:28:18,642
Are you kidding?
Where should we go first?

557
00:28:18,810 --> 00:28:22,480
 Mr. Peabody says
I'm not allowed to
drive it till I'm older.

558
00:28:22,647 --> 00:28:24,899
Do you do everything
Mr. Peabody says?

559
00:28:25,067 --> 00:28:26,150
Yeah.

560
00:28:26,318 --> 00:28:28,110
You know what that
makes you, Sherman.

561
00:28:28,278 --> 00:28:30,112
An obedient son?

562
00:28:30,280 --> 00:28:31,405
Nope.

563
00:28:31,490 --> 00:28:32,782
A dog.

564
00:28:46,004 --> 00:28:47,838
Ooh!
Nice control.

565
00:28:48,673 --> 00:28:50,299
Look at him go!
Take it, Patty!

566
00:28:51,468 --> 00:28:52,676
 Heads up, Paul!
Whoa!

567
00:28:52,969 --> 00:28:55,262
Here you go. Zing!

568
00:28:59,518 --> 00:29:01,268
Oh, yeah.

569
00:29:02,104 --> 00:29:03,687
Oh! 
Hey, look at that.

570
00:29:03,855 --> 00:29:05,439
This is fun!

571
00:29:08,360 --> 00:29:11,320
This is a little
homespun concoction
I like to call...

572
00:29:12,697 --> 00:29:14,198
"Einstein on the Beach."

573
00:29:14,366 --> 00:29:15,616
 Yummy.

574
00:29:18,120 --> 00:29:19,203
To the kids.

575
00:29:19,371 --> 00:29:21,163
 To the kids!

576
00:29:22,040 --> 00:29:23,541
Mr. Peabody.

577
00:29:23,792 --> 00:29:25,000
Sherman?

578
00:29:25,127 --> 00:29:26,293
Can I talk to
you a second?

579
00:29:26,378 --> 00:29:27,545
Of course.

580
00:29:27,629 --> 00:29:29,004
Excuse me.

581
00:29:33,468 --> 00:29:35,136
I've really hit it off
with Penny's parents.

582
00:29:35,303 --> 00:29:38,347
I think we can file this night
under "Unqualified Success."

583
00:29:38,515 --> 00:29:41,225
Uh, I would hold off
filing it just yet.

584
00:29:41,393 --> 00:29:43,727
What do you mean?
Where's Penny?

585
00:29:43,895 --> 00:29:45,855
Uh... Ancient Egypt.

586
00:29:45,981 --> 00:29:48,232
 You used the WABAC?

587
00:29:49,568 --> 00:29:51,861
 What's happening,
big guy? We're running low.

588
00:29:54,698 --> 00:29:56,699
I'll be right there, Paul.

589
00:29:56,867 --> 00:29:58,033
How could you do
such a thing?

590
00:29:58,118 --> 00:29:59,243
She called me a liar...

591
00:29:59,327 --> 00:30:00,452
for saying
George Washington

592
00:30:00,537 --> 00:30:02,329
never cut down
a cherry tree.

593
00:30:02,497 --> 00:30:04,748
So, you took her
to see George Washington?

594
00:30:04,916 --> 00:30:06,917
Yeah. She was into it.

595
00:30:07,085 --> 00:30:08,586
 Hey, Pea-buddy.

596
00:30:08,753 --> 00:30:09,753
Hey.

597
00:30:09,880 --> 00:30:10,838
Where's Penny?

598
00:30:10,922 --> 00:30:12,381
Playing hide-and-seek.
Pooping.

599
00:30:12,549 --> 00:30:14,383
Pooping.
Playing hide and seek.

600
00:30:16,052 --> 00:30:17,845
Well, which is it?
Uh...

601
00:30:18,597 --> 00:30:19,889
Hey, what's going on here?

602
00:30:20,056 --> 00:30:21,724
Yeah. What's going on here?

603
00:30:21,892 --> 00:30:23,184
What have you done with Penny?
Penny?

604
00:30:23,351 --> 00:30:24,852
Penny? Penny!

605
00:30:25,020 --> 00:30:26,937
Oh, my gosh!
Where's our daughter?

606
00:30:27,189 --> 00:30:29,648
It's hard to say, Paul.

607
00:30:29,858 --> 00:30:34,778
She could be here, or here,
or here, or here...

608
00:30:34,946 --> 00:30:36,155
or here.

609
00:30:38,074 --> 00:30:39,366
That will hold them.

610
00:30:39,534 --> 00:30:40,784
I learned that
trick from a swami

611
00:30:40,952 --> 00:30:42,203
at the Begawan Giri
in Ubud, Bali.

612
00:30:42,370 --> 00:30:43,704
Let's go!

613
00:30:57,761 --> 00:31:00,721
 Ancient Egypt.
Land of the Pharaohs.

614
00:31:00,805 --> 00:31:03,641
A beacon of progress
on the horizon of humanity...

615
00:31:03,808 --> 00:31:07,478
but a cruel and
barbarous civilization
just the same.

616
00:31:07,646 --> 00:31:10,648
I just hope
Penny isn't suffering
too badly.

617
00:31:22,494 --> 00:31:23,827
 I got it.

618
00:31:24,079 --> 00:31:25,287
What are you doing here?

619
00:31:25,455 --> 00:31:27,331
We have come
to take you home.

620
00:31:27,999 --> 00:31:30,167
Ugh! What's the Egyptian word
for "tattletale"?

621
00:31:31,586 --> 00:31:34,296
But that's beside the point.
Get your clothes on,
we're going home.

622
00:31:34,464 --> 00:31:36,507
Who died and
made you Pharaoh?

623
00:31:36,675 --> 00:31:38,592
Now, bring on
the mani-pedi.

624
00:31:39,135 --> 00:31:41,804
See, Mr. Peabody?
Lmpossible!

625
00:31:41,972 --> 00:31:43,681
Indeed,
but watch what happens...

626
00:31:43,848 --> 00:31:47,101
when an immovable object
meets an irresistible force.

627
00:31:47,560 --> 00:31:48,602
Penny...

628
00:31:48,687 --> 00:31:50,813
come here, right now.
Penny, come!

629
00:31:50,981 --> 00:31:52,690
I'm not Penny anymore.

630
00:31:52,857 --> 00:31:57,361
Now, I'm Princess Hatsheput,
precious flower of the Nile.

631
00:31:57,529 --> 00:31:58,612
"Precious," perhaps,
but if you think

632
00:31:58,738 --> 00:31:59,863
"we're going to
leave you here...

633
00:32:00,031 --> 00:32:02,283
you are most
definitely in "de-Nile."

634
00:32:03,952 --> 00:32:05,119
I don't get it.

635
00:32:05,203 --> 00:32:06,203
Now, come along.

636
00:32:06,371 --> 00:32:07,663
 Unhand her!

637
00:32:08,832 --> 00:32:11,333
What's the matter,
my sweet little
desert blossom?

638
00:32:11,501 --> 00:32:13,711
Are these barbarians
bothering you?

639
00:32:13,878 --> 00:32:16,463
As a matter of
fact, they are.

640
00:32:16,631 --> 00:32:18,048
Bow, barbarians.

641
00:32:18,216 --> 00:32:20,217
As you wish, Your Highness.

642
00:32:20,385 --> 00:32:22,219
Who's that, Mr. Peabody?

643
00:32:22,387 --> 00:32:24,805
That, Sherman, is
the living image of Amun...

644
00:32:24,973 --> 00:32:28,058
son of Akhenaten,
lord of the 18th Dynasty
of the New Kingdom...

645
00:32:28,226 --> 00:32:29,351
King Tutankhamun.

646
00:32:29,519 --> 00:32:31,312
Otherwise known
as "King Tut."

647
00:32:31,396 --> 00:32:32,521
My boyfriend.

648
00:32:32,564 --> 00:32:35,316
King Tut is
your boyfriend?
Mmm-hmm.

649
00:32:35,400 --> 00:32:37,735
Would you like me
to have them skinned,
covered with honey...

650
00:32:37,902 --> 00:32:40,195
and laid in
a pit of fire ants?

651
00:32:40,905 --> 00:32:42,323
You would do that for me?

652
00:32:42,490 --> 00:32:45,576
Anything, my desert flower.
Consider it a wedding gift.

653
00:32:45,744 --> 00:32:48,203
What? You can't
marry this guy!

654
00:32:48,288 --> 00:32:49,330
Why not?

655
00:32:49,414 --> 00:32:52,207
Well, for one,
his name rhymes
with "butt."

656
00:32:52,375 --> 00:32:55,336
I don't care.
I'm gonna have a big,
fat, Egyptian wedding.

657
00:32:55,503 --> 00:32:57,755
Spoiler alert,
King Tut dies young.

658
00:32:57,922 --> 00:32:59,757
Are you sure you've
thought this through?

659
00:32:59,924 --> 00:33:02,259
Oh, trust me,
I've thought it through.
I'm getting everything.

660
00:33:02,427 --> 00:33:04,178
The royal astronomers
have decreed...

661
00:33:04,554 --> 00:33:07,473
the wedding must take
place tomorrow at dawn.

662
00:33:07,557 --> 00:33:08,599
Who is he?

663
00:33:08,683 --> 00:33:09,892
He is Ay.
He is you?

664
00:33:10,060 --> 00:33:12,895
I am Ay. The Grand Vizier.

665
00:33:13,271 --> 00:33:15,105
Yeah, that's his name.
Oh.

666
00:33:15,357 --> 00:33:18,400
Oh, Grand Vizier,
would you mind telling
the precious princess, here...

667
00:33:18,568 --> 00:33:21,111
precisely what it means
to marry the young Pharaoh.

668
00:33:21,279 --> 00:33:22,279
Gladly.

669
00:33:22,447 --> 00:33:25,616
It means she
will be bound to him
in eternity...

670
00:33:25,784 --> 00:33:27,451
through the sacred
ceremonies

671
00:33:27,535 --> 00:33:30,454
of disembowelment
and mummification...

672
00:33:30,789 --> 00:33:32,748
as described in
the holy texts.

673
00:33:33,124 --> 00:33:34,458
Um, hold up a second.

674
00:33:34,626 --> 00:33:36,293
Can you walk me
through that, somebody?

675
00:33:36,461 --> 00:33:39,546
What he means, Penny,
is that when I die
they'll kill you, too.

676
00:33:39,714 --> 00:33:42,383
And then they'll rip out
your organs, stuff them
in canopic jars...

677
00:33:42,550 --> 00:33:44,093
and then mummify
whatever is left.

678
00:33:44,260 --> 00:33:45,302
Okay, I'm seeing this now.

679
00:33:45,470 --> 00:33:48,263
Thank you.
I'm going to go with them.

680
00:33:48,390 --> 00:33:51,308
There's no turning back now.

681
00:33:51,601 --> 00:33:52,601
To the palace!

682
00:33:52,769 --> 00:33:54,603
Let the wedding
preparations begin!

683
00:33:55,105 --> 00:33:57,231
Mr. Peabody! Sherman!

684
00:33:57,399 --> 00:33:58,399
Do something!

685
00:33:58,566 --> 00:33:59,566
Don't worry, Penny!

686
00:33:59,734 --> 00:34:00,901
We'll save you!

687
00:34:05,407 --> 00:34:06,990
Hey, wait! You can't just...

688
00:34:08,201 --> 00:34:09,868
Leave us here.

689
00:34:10,328 --> 00:34:11,495
Mr. Peabody?

690
00:34:11,663 --> 00:34:12,704
Yes, Sherman?

691
00:34:12,872 --> 00:34:13,997
 Can
I hold your hand?

692
00:34:14,165 --> 00:34:15,874
 Of course you can.

693
00:34:16,042 --> 00:34:18,502
Boy, your hand
is cold, Mr. Peabody.

694
00:34:18,670 --> 00:34:20,170
Sherman?
Yeah?

695
00:34:21,673 --> 00:34:22,673
That's not my hand.

696
00:34:29,055 --> 00:34:30,681
That's disarming.

697
00:34:30,849 --> 00:34:33,767
Now, to find
a way out of here.

698
00:34:33,852 --> 00:34:34,935
Yuck!

699
00:34:35,019 --> 00:34:36,353
Look around, Sherman.

700
00:34:36,521 --> 00:34:38,689
These tombs
are lined with
hieroglyphics...

701
00:34:38,857 --> 00:34:40,983
designed to assist
the pharaohs' souls

702
00:34:41,109 --> 00:34:43,235
in their journey
to the afterlife.

703
00:34:43,403 --> 00:34:46,530
And they may
assist us as well.

704
00:34:48,533 --> 00:34:50,117
Oh, this depicts
the god Anubis

705
00:34:50,201 --> 00:34:52,286
sailing the boat of Ra
to the underworld.

706
00:34:52,454 --> 00:34:55,914
It appears the boats of Ra
are the key to our escape.

707
00:34:56,082 --> 00:34:58,208
We must find them in time
to stop the wedding.

708
00:34:58,376 --> 00:35:00,919
Well, if you ask me,
we should let her
marry that guy.

709
00:35:01,087 --> 00:35:02,254
They deserve each other.

710
00:35:02,422 --> 00:35:03,589
What's that, Sherman?

711
00:35:03,756 --> 00:35:05,215
Tut? Give me a break.

712
00:35:05,383 --> 00:35:08,594
Bald, wears a skirt,
and makeup.

713
00:35:08,761 --> 00:35:11,305
If I didn't know
any better, Sherman,
I would say you were jealous.

714
00:35:11,473 --> 00:35:13,265
Jealous? Of what?

715
00:35:13,433 --> 00:35:15,225
Tut's affection
for Penny, of course.

716
00:35:15,393 --> 00:35:16,810
You think I like Penny?

717
00:35:17,061 --> 00:35:18,228
Mmm-hmm.

718
00:35:18,438 --> 00:35:19,563
Give me a break!

719
00:35:19,731 --> 00:35:24,401
It's not like I
want to hold her hand,
or go to the park...

720
00:35:24,569 --> 00:35:27,404
or watch her while
she's brushing her hair.

721
00:35:30,325 --> 00:35:31,742
Or anything.

722
00:35:32,118 --> 00:35:33,243
Hmm.

723
00:35:34,537 --> 00:35:35,996
A-ha!

724
00:35:38,625 --> 00:35:40,167
Quickly, Sherman.

725
00:35:43,463 --> 00:35:45,756
Ah, ah, ah!
Careful, Sherman.

726
00:35:46,007 --> 00:35:47,591
It's a booby trap.

727
00:35:47,717 --> 00:35:49,968
What's so funny?

728
00:35:50,053 --> 00:35:51,428
You said "booby."

729
00:35:53,515 --> 00:35:56,016
One wrong step
and we're done for.

730
00:35:57,769 --> 00:35:58,852
"The boat...

731
00:35:59,020 --> 00:36:01,522
"of Ra sails straight...

732
00:36:01,940 --> 00:36:02,940
"to day.

733
00:36:03,107 --> 00:36:06,652
"Take the wrong boat...

734
00:36:06,819 --> 00:36:08,111
man will pay."

735
00:36:08,279 --> 00:36:09,530
All right, Sherman,
now it's your turn.

736
00:36:09,822 --> 00:36:12,366
Do the puzzle
exactly as I did.

737
00:36:12,450 --> 00:36:13,492
Huh?

738
00:36:13,576 --> 00:36:15,202
Think it through,
one step at a time.

739
00:36:19,707 --> 00:36:21,500
The boat of Ra
sails straight...

740
00:36:21,668 --> 00:36:22,668
 play.

741
00:36:23,628 --> 00:36:24,711
Uh, I mean, "pay."

742
00:36:24,879 --> 00:36:25,963
Oh, my.

743
00:36:29,467 --> 00:36:30,676
Uh-oh.

744
00:36:33,346 --> 00:36:34,388
 Run!

745
00:36:39,852 --> 00:36:41,395
The boats of Ra!

746
00:36:41,563 --> 00:36:43,480
One boat is the way out,
the other will send us...

747
00:36:43,648 --> 00:36:45,232
plunging into darkness
and certain death.

748
00:36:45,400 --> 00:36:46,733
What?

749
00:36:46,901 --> 00:36:47,901
Sherman, get in the boat.

750
00:36:48,069 --> 00:36:50,988
As soon as I move
these blocks together,
it's going to move very fast.

751
00:36:51,155 --> 00:36:52,239
Which boat, Mr. Peabody?

752
00:36:52,365 --> 00:36:53,407
What?

753
00:36:53,575 --> 00:36:56,159
Which boat
is the "not-certain-
death-plunge" boat?

754
00:36:56,327 --> 00:36:57,494
That one!

755
00:37:11,175 --> 00:37:12,342
We did it, Sherman!

756
00:37:12,427 --> 00:37:13,510
Sherman?

757
00:37:13,595 --> 00:37:15,262
Mr. Peabody!

758
00:37:15,430 --> 00:37:16,722
What are you
doing over there?

759
00:37:16,889 --> 00:37:19,099
I thought you
pointed to this one!

760
00:37:28,860 --> 00:37:30,360
Ahhh!

761
00:37:44,542 --> 00:37:46,585
Sherman? Sherman?

762
00:37:46,753 --> 00:37:48,211
Are you all right?

763
00:37:48,921 --> 00:37:50,547
 I'm good.

764
00:38:03,478 --> 00:38:05,228
The sun god, Ra...

765
00:38:05,396 --> 00:38:09,983
commands us to begin
the sacred ceremony!

766
00:38:20,119 --> 00:38:23,747
Bring forth the blade
for the blood oath.

767
00:38:27,919 --> 00:38:32,673
Where blade meets flesh
in this sacred rite...

768
00:38:35,301 --> 00:38:36,593
We pay tribute...

769
00:38:36,761 --> 00:38:38,929
to the sun god, Ra!

770
00:38:39,681 --> 00:38:40,931
 Wait!

771
00:38:42,642 --> 00:38:43,684
 Anubis!

772
00:38:43,768 --> 00:38:44,935
The god of death!

773
00:38:45,103 --> 00:38:47,270
 The wedding
must not continue.

774
00:38:47,438 --> 00:38:49,314
Why, Anubis, why?

775
00:38:49,482 --> 00:38:51,983
Plagues. Plagues!

776
00:38:52,318 --> 00:38:54,486
If this marriage
pact is sealed...

777
00:38:54,654 --> 00:38:58,490
I will shower
down upon the land
uncountable plagues.

778
00:38:58,658 --> 00:39:00,158
Oy, again
with the plagues!

779
00:39:00,326 --> 00:39:02,327
Why did I ever
move to Egypt?

780
00:39:02,495 --> 00:39:05,622
But, Anubis,
the sun god, Ra,
has decreed...

781
00:39:05,790 --> 00:39:08,458
that this girl
is to be
the boy-king's wife.

782
00:39:08,835 --> 00:39:10,293
That's so funny.

783
00:39:10,461 --> 00:39:13,672
I was talking to
the sun god, Ra,
just the other day...

784
00:39:13,840 --> 00:39:16,466
and he told me
he changed his mind.

785
00:39:16,551 --> 00:39:17,551
Really?

786
00:39:17,635 --> 00:39:21,555
Old "Flip-Flop Ra,"
we call him here
in the underworld.

787
00:39:21,723 --> 00:39:24,891
But it's too late.
We've already paid
for the catering.

788
00:39:26,519 --> 00:39:29,855
Too bad!
You're going to
lose your deposit.

789
00:39:32,358 --> 00:39:35,819
More smoke, Sherman.
This canine
subterfuge is working.

790
00:39:35,987 --> 00:39:37,154
Deliver the girl...

791
00:39:37,321 --> 00:39:40,198
to the gates of the city,
and leave her there...

792
00:39:40,366 --> 00:39:43,493
where the gods
will retrieve her forthwith.

793
00:39:43,661 --> 00:39:47,664
Only in this
manner may the plagues
upon this land be avoided.

794
00:39:47,832 --> 00:39:49,833
 The girl must go!

795
00:39:51,294 --> 00:39:52,335
Ow!

796
00:39:52,420 --> 00:39:54,171
Anubis has spoken!

797
00:39:54,338 --> 00:39:56,548
Take this girl to the gates!

798
00:39:56,674 --> 00:39:57,841
Ow.

799
00:40:03,181 --> 00:40:05,724
Anubis, you sound unwell.

800
00:40:05,892 --> 00:40:08,393
Well, I have been feeling
a little under the weather...

801
00:40:08,561 --> 00:40:11,188
but I'm feeling
much better now.

802
00:40:11,898 --> 00:40:13,106
Thank you.

803
00:40:15,109 --> 00:40:16,777
Phew! Huh?

804
00:40:24,368 --> 00:40:26,161
Penny, Sherman, quickly.

805
00:40:26,245 --> 00:40:27,329
Come on, Penny.

806
00:40:27,413 --> 00:40:28,580
Sherman!

807
00:40:30,374 --> 00:40:31,833
Ah!

808
00:40:34,378 --> 00:40:35,754
Runaway bride!

809
00:40:35,922 --> 00:40:37,464
Stop them, you fools!

810
00:40:40,510 --> 00:40:41,510
Ah!

811
00:40:57,443 --> 00:40:59,569
Penny, Sherman,
climb aboard.

812
00:41:00,738 --> 00:41:02,197
Whoo-hoo!

813
00:41:09,914 --> 00:41:11,915
They're getting away!

814
00:41:12,583 --> 00:41:13,583
Ah!

815
00:41:22,718 --> 00:41:24,386
Whoa!

816
00:41:27,598 --> 00:41:29,307
I got it.

817
00:41:31,561 --> 00:41:33,186
Whoo-hoo! We made it.

818
00:41:33,312 --> 00:41:35,146
 Where do we
go next, Mr. Peabody?
Home.

819
00:41:35,314 --> 00:41:36,940
We've got to get back
to the dinner party...

820
00:41:37,108 --> 00:41:38,984
before Penny's parents
realize she's missing.

821
00:41:39,151 --> 00:41:41,486
We don't have to
mention the whole...

822
00:41:41,654 --> 00:41:43,530
uh, King Tut
wedding thing, right?

823
00:41:43,614 --> 00:41:44,865
Certainly not.

824
00:41:44,949 --> 00:41:46,658
Anyway,
as far as I'm concerned,

825
00:41:46,784 --> 00:41:48,493
they get married too
young in Ancient Egypt.

826
00:41:48,661 --> 00:41:51,538
Or, perhaps,
I'm just some old "Giza."

827
00:41:53,416 --> 00:41:54,624
Huh?

828
00:41:55,793 --> 00:41:56,835
 Warning.

829
00:41:57,336 --> 00:41:59,462
WABAC power
supply insufficient.

830
00:41:59,630 --> 00:42:02,048
Charge now. Warning.

831
00:42:02,216 --> 00:42:03,800
Uh, what's the matter,
Mr. Peabody?

832
00:42:03,968 --> 00:42:06,678
All this zipping about
the cosmos has drained
our power supply.

833
00:42:06,846 --> 00:42:08,972
We're going to have to
make an unscheduled stop.

834
00:42:09,265 --> 00:42:10,390
As luck would have it...

835
00:42:10,474 --> 00:42:12,559
we have just enough
power to make it
to the Renaissance.

836
00:42:25,656 --> 00:42:29,159
I can't even
tell my left brain
from my right anymore!

837
00:42:29,327 --> 00:42:31,328
How many times
I got to tell you,
Mona Lisa?

838
00:42:31,495 --> 00:42:32,454
Mona Lisa?

839
00:42:32,538 --> 00:42:34,664
 I can't
paint the picture...

840
00:42:34,832 --> 00:42:36,750
until you smile!

841
00:42:36,918 --> 00:42:40,503
Leonardo, tell me one thing
I have to smile about.

842
00:42:40,671 --> 00:42:42,422
The sunshine, the pasta.

843
00:42:42,590 --> 00:42:46,426
All the things that make
Italy such a popular
tourist destination!

844
00:42:46,594 --> 00:42:49,387
But I have not
seen any of them,
Leonardo!

845
00:42:49,555 --> 00:42:52,849
Because I'm
sitting here all day
on my abbondanza!

846
00:42:53,684 --> 00:42:56,436
I don't think
that means
"chair" in Italian.

847
00:42:56,520 --> 00:42:59,689
Ah, Peabody, my old friend.

848
00:42:59,857 --> 00:43:02,275
What a welcome
interruption!

849
00:43:02,443 --> 00:43:06,029
Believe you me,
this woman is
making me nuts.

850
00:43:06,197 --> 00:43:07,781
So, how you been?

851
00:43:07,949 --> 00:43:09,741
Good to see you.
What do you want?

852
00:43:09,909 --> 00:43:11,701
We're in a desperate
hurry to get home,

853
00:43:11,827 --> 00:43:13,578
but the WABAC
needs a jump start...

854
00:43:13,746 --> 00:43:16,039
and we thought,
who better than

855
00:43:16,165 --> 00:43:18,375
Leonardo da Vinci to
help us on our way?

856
00:43:18,542 --> 00:43:20,961
Peabody,
I would love to help you,

857
00:43:21,087 --> 00:43:23,463
but you come at
a very bad time.

858
00:43:23,631 --> 00:43:26,716
I don't know
what I'm going to do
with this crazy woman.

859
00:43:28,260 --> 00:43:29,302
You see what I mean?

860
00:43:29,428 --> 00:43:30,470
What seems to be the problem?

861
00:43:30,638 --> 00:43:31,972
"What is the problem?"

862
00:43:32,139 --> 00:43:34,724
I am halfway done
with the painting,
she won't even smile.

863
00:43:34,892 --> 00:43:37,769
Fine. I smile.

864
00:43:40,231 --> 00:43:42,565
No! That's a fake smile!

865
00:43:42,733 --> 00:43:44,067
Everybody knows that!

866
00:43:44,235 --> 00:43:46,486
Why don't you
make it a real smile?

867
00:43:46,654 --> 00:43:48,113
Why don't you say
something funny?

868
00:43:48,280 --> 00:43:49,739
I paint the paintings.

869
00:43:49,907 --> 00:43:51,741
I make the machines.

870
00:43:51,909 --> 00:43:54,661
I don't tell the jokes!

871
00:43:54,829 --> 00:43:57,414
Perhaps, I can be
of assistance. You see...

872
00:43:57,581 --> 00:43:59,624
humor is not immune
to the laws of science.

873
00:43:59,792 --> 00:44:01,584
Using algorithms,
we can extrapolate

874
00:44:01,711 --> 00:44:03,461
what is universally
considered "funny"...

875
00:44:03,629 --> 00:44:05,755
thus producing
a formula that is

876
00:44:05,881 --> 00:44:07,924
scientifically
certain to cause laughter.

877
00:44:08,342 --> 00:44:10,927
Case in point,
the pratfall.

878
00:44:16,767 --> 00:44:18,977
Is everyone amused?

879
00:44:20,938 --> 00:44:22,188
Hmm.

880
00:44:22,273 --> 00:44:23,857
The data
was so clear. Ooh!

881
00:44:24,025 --> 00:44:25,316
Don't worry, Mr. Peabody.

882
00:44:25,484 --> 00:44:26,818
I got it!
Sherman... Ahh!

883
00:44:26,902 --> 00:44:29,070
Oh!

884
00:44:42,460 --> 00:44:43,793
Hold that smile!

885
00:44:43,961 --> 00:44:45,962
Hold it right there!
No move! No move!

886
00:44:54,013 --> 00:44:56,723
 Well, Leo, if my
calculations are correct...

887
00:44:56,891 --> 00:44:59,517
this machine of
ours should generate
enough centrifugal force...

888
00:44:59,685 --> 00:45:00,894
to send us home.

889
00:45:01,062 --> 00:45:03,480
I got one last piece
I gotta pound in place.

890
00:45:03,647 --> 00:45:06,816
Sherman, why don't
you fetch the hammer
for Mr. Da Vinci?

891
00:45:06,984 --> 00:45:08,818
Okay, Mr. Peabody.

892
00:45:13,491 --> 00:45:14,616
Mr. Peabody!

893
00:45:14,700 --> 00:45:15,825
Well done, Sherman.

894
00:45:15,993 --> 00:45:16,993
But, Mr. Peabody!

895
00:45:17,161 --> 00:45:18,495
Very helpful.

896
00:45:33,010 --> 00:45:34,177
Sherman!

897
00:45:34,678 --> 00:45:36,179
Yes, Mr. Peabody?

898
00:45:36,889 --> 00:45:38,098
The hammer.

899
00:45:38,599 --> 00:45:39,766
Da Vinci.

900
00:45:39,892 --> 00:45:42,310
Oh. Okay, Mr. Peabody.

901
00:45:43,687 --> 00:45:45,355
Oh!

902
00:45:46,190 --> 00:45:47,607
Here you go, Mr. Da Vinci.
Ahh!

903
00:45:47,775 --> 00:45:48,858
Do you need any help?

904
00:45:49,026 --> 00:45:50,860
No, no.
That's quite all right.

905
00:45:51,028 --> 00:45:52,529
Thank you.

906
00:45:53,280 --> 00:45:54,280
Psst! Sherman.

907
00:45:54,740 --> 00:45:57,033
Huh?
Let's go. Let's go explore.

908
00:45:57,701 --> 00:45:59,744
Uh, well, I'm supposed
to be having

909
00:45:59,870 --> 00:46:01,913
father-son time
with Mr. Peabody.

910
00:46:02,081 --> 00:46:03,748
Wouldn't you rather
have fun with me?

911
00:46:03,916 --> 00:46:05,083
Uh...

912
00:46:05,292 --> 00:46:06,334
Okay.

913
00:46:06,418 --> 00:46:07,460
Sherman...

914
00:46:07,628 --> 00:46:08,711
where are you going?

915
00:46:08,879 --> 00:46:09,963
Exploring.

916
00:46:10,131 --> 00:46:11,256
But we need your help.

917
00:46:11,423 --> 00:46:13,925
No, we don't!
I mean, we can manage.

918
00:46:14,093 --> 00:46:15,218
 Somehow.

919
00:46:15,803 --> 00:46:17,095
He's a boy, Peabody.

920
00:46:17,263 --> 00:46:19,889
Let him have his fun.
Let him go.

921
00:46:20,057 --> 00:46:21,724
Thanks, Mr. Peabody!

922
00:46:25,312 --> 00:46:27,438
He's growing up, Peabody.

923
00:46:27,606 --> 00:46:30,650
Like a baby bird
leaving the nest.

924
00:46:30,901 --> 00:46:33,236
Isn't it wonderful?

925
00:46:40,244 --> 00:46:42,412
It's like a museum.

926
00:46:43,247 --> 00:46:45,748
It's like a toy store.

927
00:46:50,588 --> 00:46:52,255
Wow.

928
00:46:56,093 --> 00:46:57,260
 Check this out.

929
00:46:57,428 --> 00:46:59,929
It's the world's
biggest model airplane.

930
00:47:00,097 --> 00:47:02,765
It's not a model, Penny.
It's a prototype.

931
00:47:02,933 --> 00:47:05,935
And we should probably
just leave that alone.

932
00:47:06,061 --> 00:47:07,020
Okay.

933
00:47:07,104 --> 00:47:09,189
But wouldn't it be cool
if we could fly it?

934
00:47:09,356 --> 00:47:11,357
I don't think
Mr. Peabody would like that.

935
00:47:11,525 --> 00:47:13,610
Well, Mr. Peabody
isn't here.

936
00:47:13,777 --> 00:47:15,320
Just tell me how it works.

937
00:47:15,487 --> 00:47:16,696
Please?

938
00:47:16,947 --> 00:47:18,156
For learning.

939
00:47:18,282 --> 00:47:19,991
Oh. Okay.

940
00:47:20,784 --> 00:47:23,953
The thrust comes from
this kind of crossbow
doohickey here.

941
00:47:24,121 --> 00:47:28,124
Then it shoots along
the track until the wind
catches the wings.

942
00:47:28,292 --> 00:47:30,043
But how does it go?
Huh?

943
00:47:30,211 --> 00:47:31,628
How do you take off?

944
00:47:31,795 --> 00:47:33,880
Oh, you just
pull down that lever.

945
00:47:35,132 --> 00:47:36,382
This one?

946
00:47:36,550 --> 00:47:37,675
Oh, boy.

947
00:47:37,760 --> 00:47:39,302
 Ah!

948
00:47:41,722 --> 00:47:44,766
Wow! Whoo-hoo!

949
00:47:46,352 --> 00:47:47,977
 This is crazy!

950
00:47:48,145 --> 00:47:50,396
No, it's not Sherman.
It's fun!

951
00:47:50,564 --> 00:47:51,856
We're gonna die!

952
00:47:52,024 --> 00:47:54,817
Oh, stop being
such a party pooper and
enjoy it! (LAUGHING)

953
00:48:00,157 --> 00:48:01,407
Ah...

954
00:48:01,492 --> 00:48:04,327
Nothing is as beautiful
as an elegant equation...

955
00:48:04,495 --> 00:48:07,163
translated into
perfect engineering.

956
00:48:07,331 --> 00:48:09,332
Why can't children
be so simple?

957
00:48:09,500 --> 00:48:12,502
Because children
are not machines, Peabody.

958
00:48:12,670 --> 00:48:15,880
Believe me,
I tried to build one.

959
00:48:16,048 --> 00:48:18,174
Oh! It was creepy.

960
00:48:20,594 --> 00:48:22,220
Here, Sherman!
You fly it!

961
00:48:22,388 --> 00:48:23,680
But I don't want to fly!

962
00:48:23,847 --> 00:48:25,682
Sure you do. It'll be fun!

963
00:48:25,849 --> 00:48:28,434
No, seriously, Penny,
I don't want to!

964
00:48:28,602 --> 00:48:30,353
I'm letting go. One...

965
00:48:30,521 --> 00:48:31,562
Don't let go!

966
00:48:31,689 --> 00:48:32,689
Two...

967
00:48:32,773 --> 00:48:34,274
No!
Three!

968
00:48:37,528 --> 00:48:38,695
Penny, fly the plane!

969
00:48:39,196 --> 00:48:40,321
No, Sherman!

970
00:48:40,447 --> 00:48:41,531
You're going to
have to save us!

971
00:48:41,699 --> 00:48:42,740
But I can't do it!

972
00:48:43,284 --> 00:48:46,119
I'm serious, Penny.
I don't know how to fly!

973
00:48:46,287 --> 00:48:48,037
You can do it!
I know you can!

974
00:48:48,205 --> 00:48:49,247
Come on, Sherman.

975
00:48:49,415 --> 00:48:50,415
Fly!

976
00:48:57,214 --> 00:48:58,631
Ah!

977
00:49:03,554 --> 00:49:05,138
Phew!

978
00:49:16,567 --> 00:49:18,568
See? You got this,
Sherman.

979
00:49:18,736 --> 00:49:21,446
You're right.
I have got this.

980
00:49:22,031 --> 00:49:23,906
Whoo-hoo-hoo!

981
00:49:30,080 --> 00:49:31,497
Da Vinci's at it again!

982
00:49:31,665 --> 00:49:33,249
You ever see
that child he made?

983
00:49:33,417 --> 00:49:34,751
So creepy.

984
00:49:34,918 --> 00:49:36,461
Papa. Mama.
(BOTH SHUDDERING)

985
00:49:37,671 --> 00:49:39,130
Papa. Mama.

986
00:50:06,116 --> 00:50:07,533
All done up here, Leonardo.

987
00:50:07,701 --> 00:50:09,869
And I am all done
down here.

988
00:50:10,037 --> 00:50:11,788
It is beautiful, isn't it?

989
00:50:11,955 --> 00:50:16,125
Every piece in its place
doing precisely what
it's supposed to do.

990
00:50:16,293 --> 00:50:17,710
Look, Peabody!

991
00:50:17,878 --> 00:50:19,796
It's my flying mach...

992
00:50:19,963 --> 00:50:21,297
My flying machine?

993
00:50:21,548 --> 00:50:22,548
Sherman.

994
00:50:22,633 --> 00:50:23,633
Sherman?

995
00:50:23,801 --> 00:50:26,052
Sherman, what are
you doing up there?

996
00:50:26,220 --> 00:50:27,637
I'm flying!

997
00:50:27,805 --> 00:50:30,431
But, Sherman,
you don't know how to fly!

998
00:50:30,516 --> 00:50:31,557
I don't?

999
00:50:31,642 --> 00:50:32,642
No!

1000
00:50:39,149 --> 00:50:40,233
Turn!

1001
00:50:40,317 --> 00:50:41,317
Turn, Sherman!

1002
00:50:41,402 --> 00:50:43,528
Lean!

1003
00:50:46,990 --> 00:50:48,825
Oh, no!

1004
00:50:57,668 --> 00:50:59,877
Sherman! Are you okay?

1005
00:51:00,045 --> 00:51:02,713
That was pretty fantastic!

1006
00:51:03,841 --> 00:51:06,050
Oh! I can't believe it!

1007
00:51:07,010 --> 00:51:09,262
My flying machine!
It's work!

1008
00:51:09,638 --> 00:51:13,808
 Sherman!
You are the first flying man!

1009
00:51:14,017 --> 00:51:15,893
Oh, you should be
very proud, Peabody.

1010
00:51:16,061 --> 00:51:17,728
Very, very proud!

1011
00:51:17,896 --> 00:51:20,022
"Proud" doesn't
begin to describe it.

1012
00:51:21,859 --> 00:51:24,360
Leonardo, will you please
fire up the mechanism?

1013
00:51:43,046 --> 00:51:46,632
Papa. Mama.

1014
00:51:46,800 --> 00:51:48,593
Mona!

1015
00:51:50,220 --> 00:51:51,220
Papa. Mama.

1016
00:51:51,305 --> 00:51:52,305
The kid!

1017
00:52:18,832 --> 00:52:21,417
I'm sorry I broke
the plane, Mr. Peabody.

1018
00:52:21,585 --> 00:52:24,128
Well, you should be.
You could have been killed.

1019
00:52:24,296 --> 00:52:25,630
What are you
talking about?

1020
00:52:25,797 --> 00:52:28,466
Sherman flew a plane.
He was amazing!

1021
00:52:28,634 --> 00:52:32,053
Sherman destroyed
a priceless
historical artifact.

1022
00:52:32,221 --> 00:52:34,388
Whatever. You
should be happy.

1023
00:52:34,556 --> 00:52:37,099
It turns out Sherman
is not a complete and
total loser, after all.

1024
00:52:37,267 --> 00:52:38,476
Yeah, Mr. Peabody.

1025
00:52:38,560 --> 00:52:41,229
It turns out I'm not
a complete and
total loser, after all.

1026
00:52:42,981 --> 00:52:44,023
Ms. Peterson...

1027
00:52:44,107 --> 00:52:46,651
stop turning my son
into a hooligan.

1028
00:52:46,777 --> 00:52:48,069
It's not my fault
he's a hooligan.

1029
00:52:48,237 --> 00:52:50,738
Yeah, it's not her
fault I'm a hooligan.

1030
00:52:50,906 --> 00:52:52,281
Well, it's certainly
not my fault!

1031
00:52:52,449 --> 00:52:53,866
I've spent
the last seven years

1032
00:52:53,992 --> 00:52:55,409
teaching Sherman
good judgment.

1033
00:52:55,577 --> 00:52:56,619
If you're such
a great parent...

1034
00:52:56,703 --> 00:52:59,288
why is Ms. Grunion
trying to take
Sherman away from you?

1035
00:53:02,334 --> 00:53:03,834
Is that true?

1036
00:53:04,002 --> 00:53:06,087
Is someone gonna
take me away from you?

1037
00:53:06,255 --> 00:53:08,589
No, Sherman,
I'll never let that happen.

1038
00:53:08,757 --> 00:53:10,341
You just need to trust me.

1039
00:53:10,509 --> 00:53:12,843
Oh, dear, a black hole!

1040
00:53:18,600 --> 00:53:19,934
What's happening?

1041
00:53:20,102 --> 00:53:21,352
If I can't pull
us out of here...

1042
00:53:21,520 --> 00:53:24,480
we're going to be
smashed to smithereens
on the event horizon.

1043
00:53:29,570 --> 00:53:32,280
There's not enough
power to resist
the gravitational pull!

1044
00:53:32,698 --> 00:53:35,283
I've got to divert everything
to the reverse thrusters.

1045
00:53:35,450 --> 00:53:36,450
Why didn't you tell me?

1046
00:53:36,618 --> 00:53:37,618
Tell you what?

1047
00:53:37,703 --> 00:53:39,161
Why didn't you
tell me Ms. Grunion

1048
00:53:39,329 --> 00:53:40,746
was trying to take
me away from you?

1049
00:53:41,081 --> 00:53:42,832
It's not your job to
worry about these things.

1050
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:44,542
You just didn't
think I could handle it.

1051
00:53:44,710 --> 00:53:46,794
We'll discuss it later.
Now, sit down.

1052
00:53:46,962 --> 00:53:48,838
I don't want to
discuss it later!

1053
00:53:49,006 --> 00:53:50,339
Sherman, sit!

1054
00:53:50,507 --> 00:53:52,425
You can't talk
to me like that.

1055
00:53:52,593 --> 00:53:53,843
I'm not a dog.

1056
00:53:54,011 --> 00:53:55,219
What did you say?

1057
00:53:55,387 --> 00:53:57,805
I said, I'm not a dog!

1058
00:53:58,265 --> 00:54:00,474
You're right,
Sherman, you're not.

1059
00:54:00,642 --> 00:54:02,935
You're just a very bad boy!

1060
00:54:03,353 --> 00:54:05,313
 T-minus 10...

1061
00:54:05,480 --> 00:54:07,440
Nine, eight...

1062
00:54:07,524 --> 00:54:08,608
Seven...

1063
00:54:08,692 --> 00:54:09,650
Six...

1064
00:54:09,735 --> 00:54:10,943
Five...

1065
00:54:11,028 --> 00:54:12,820
Four, three...

1066
00:54:13,655 --> 00:54:14,363
Two...

1067
00:54:14,531 --> 00:54:15,448
One.

1068
00:54:30,088 --> 00:54:31,172
Sherman?

1069
00:54:31,673 --> 00:54:32,632
Penny?

1070
00:54:33,050 --> 00:54:34,800
Sherman, are you okay?

1071
00:54:38,138 --> 00:54:39,597
Sherman?

1072
00:54:47,022 --> 00:54:48,689
He's gone.

1073
00:54:48,857 --> 00:54:50,733
Where are we, anyway?

1074
00:54:52,069 --> 00:54:53,402
 Oh, no.

1075
00:54:54,154 --> 00:54:56,864
We're on the brink
of one of history's
most ferocious conflicts...

1076
00:55:12,631 --> 00:55:13,964
 Delivery.

1077
00:55:21,682 --> 00:55:24,058
How are we doing,
heroes of Greece?

1078
00:55:24,226 --> 00:55:25,476
Feeling good?

1079
00:55:25,644 --> 00:55:27,478
Feeling strong?

1080
00:55:28,647 --> 00:55:30,231
Okay, let's get warmed up!

1081
00:55:30,399 --> 00:55:32,066
We don't want to pull
something out there.

1082
00:55:32,234 --> 00:55:34,068
Remember what
happened to Achilles.

1083
00:55:34,236 --> 00:55:36,195
That whole thing
with his heel.

1084
00:55:38,115 --> 00:55:40,199
Looking good, Diomedes.

1085
00:55:40,492 --> 00:55:42,284
Menelaus, my man!

1086
00:55:42,494 --> 00:55:43,703
My man.

1087
00:55:43,870 --> 00:55:46,122
Are you ready
to get on the field,
Shermanus?

1088
00:55:49,876 --> 00:55:50,876
That's cute.

1089
00:55:52,421 --> 00:55:54,130
Shh.

1090
00:55:56,049 --> 00:55:59,051
Odysseus,
what news do you bring?

1091
00:55:59,594 --> 00:56:01,345
Someone left this for us.

1092
00:56:01,513 --> 00:56:02,763
A present. Nice.

1093
00:56:02,931 --> 00:56:05,182
It looks just like our horse.

1094
00:56:06,393 --> 00:56:08,060
Should I bring it inside?

1095
00:56:09,438 --> 00:56:10,771
It would be rude not to.

1096
00:56:16,153 --> 00:56:17,987
I did not see that coming!

1097
00:56:18,488 --> 00:56:21,824
Ugh! Jeez Louise,
what is that smell?

1098
00:56:22,033 --> 00:56:23,909
 Oh!

1099
00:56:23,994 --> 00:56:26,078
Ooh. That is
the smell of victory.

1100
00:56:26,163 --> 00:56:28,456
Yeah! Victory!

1101
00:56:28,623 --> 00:56:31,375
Greetings, men of
Athens, Sparta and Thebes.

1102
00:56:31,543 --> 00:56:32,793
Peabody, here.

1103
00:56:32,961 --> 00:56:34,545
I've come for Sherman.

1104
00:56:34,713 --> 00:56:36,547
Do you know this guy?
I thought I did...

1105
00:56:36,715 --> 00:56:38,174
but now I'm not so sure.

1106
00:56:38,341 --> 00:56:40,468
Then he must be a spy.
Kill him!

1107
00:56:40,635 --> 00:56:42,553
No! No!

1108
00:56:43,221 --> 00:56:45,514
He's my dad.

1109
00:56:45,682 --> 00:56:46,932
Your dad?
Huh?

1110
00:56:47,100 --> 00:56:49,143
It's an adoptive
relationship.

1111
00:56:49,895 --> 00:56:51,312
Aw!

1112
00:56:51,438 --> 00:56:54,398
Thank you for
taking such good care
of my son, Agamemnon...

1113
00:56:54,566 --> 00:56:56,942
but it's time for
him to come home.

1114
00:56:57,110 --> 00:56:59,779
Sorry, Mr. Peabody,
I've joined the Greek army.

1115
00:56:59,946 --> 00:57:01,238
Shermanus is one of us now.

1116
00:57:01,406 --> 00:57:02,531
He's a brother.
I'm his brother.

1117
00:57:02,699 --> 00:57:03,699
He's my son.

1118
00:57:03,784 --> 00:57:05,034
He took an oath.
I took an oath.

1119
00:57:05,202 --> 00:57:05,910
He's seven!

1120
00:57:06,495 --> 00:57:07,995
And a half!

1121
00:57:08,330 --> 00:57:11,707
All sons must
prove themselves
to their fathers.

1122
00:57:11,875 --> 00:57:12,541
Today...

1123
00:57:12,834 --> 00:57:17,129
Shermanus will prove himself
on the field of battle.

1124
00:57:17,297 --> 00:57:18,130
But he's only a child.

1125
00:57:18,298 --> 00:57:21,342
Your dad may not think
you're ready to
become a man, Shermanus...

1126
00:57:21,510 --> 00:57:22,551
but we do.

1127
00:57:22,719 --> 00:57:23,636
 Yeah!

1128
00:57:23,762 --> 00:57:24,720
Yeah, Mr. Peabody.

1129
00:57:24,888 --> 00:57:26,680
Now, I'll show you
what I can handle.

1130
00:57:26,848 --> 00:57:29,183
FYI, a lot of heroes
have father issues.

1131
00:57:29,351 --> 00:57:30,768
My old man is a minotaur.

1132
00:57:30,936 --> 00:57:34,063
Half man,
half bull, all judgment.

1133
00:57:34,231 --> 00:57:36,357
Ajax, here, strongest
guy in the world...

1134
00:57:36,525 --> 00:57:40,069
but his father never
accepted that his real
dream was to sing.

1135
00:57:40,237 --> 00:57:41,987
I wanted to be
in the Greek chorus.

1136
00:57:42,155 --> 00:57:44,198
Uh, yeah, and
don't even get me
started about Oedipus.

1137
00:57:44,366 --> 00:57:46,200
Let's just say
that you do not want

1138
00:57:46,326 --> 00:57:48,160
to be at his house
over the holidays.

1139
00:57:48,328 --> 00:57:49,537
It's awkward.

1140
00:57:50,121 --> 00:57:51,831
Sherman, I'm concerned
you haven't
thought this through.

1141
00:57:51,998 --> 00:57:55,251
This is war.
Do you realize
what's about to happen?

1142
00:57:55,544 --> 00:57:57,002
I'll tell you
what's gonna happen.

1143
00:57:57,170 --> 00:57:59,380
We're gonna
destroy their houses!

1144
00:57:59,548 --> 00:58:00,881
Pull down their temples!

1145
00:58:01,049 --> 00:58:04,093
And make the streets
of the city run red...

1146
00:58:04,427 --> 00:58:06,262
with Trojan blood!

1147
00:58:06,429 --> 00:58:07,513
 Yeah!

1148
00:58:07,931 --> 00:58:12,142
 Blood!
Blood! Blood!

1149
00:58:21,278 --> 00:58:22,987
Zeus on three! One!

1150
00:58:23,154 --> 00:58:25,823
Sherman, I absolutely
forbid you to fight
in the Trojan War.

1151
00:58:25,991 --> 00:58:28,784
It's not fair! All my
friends are fighting
in the Trojan War.

1152
00:58:28,952 --> 00:58:30,536
Two!
Sherman, it's dangerous.

1153
00:58:30,704 --> 00:58:31,745
I'm wearing a helmet.

1154
00:58:31,913 --> 00:58:33,247
Three!
You're not going!

1155
00:58:33,415 --> 00:58:34,498
Oh, yes, I am.

1156
00:58:34,583 --> 00:58:36,292
Zeus!

1157
00:58:37,002 --> 00:58:39,044
 Zeus! Zeus!

1158
00:58:41,548 --> 00:58:44,800
Eat my bronze,
you Trojan dogs!

1159
00:58:46,845 --> 00:58:48,971
Eat my bronze,
you Trojan dog!

1160
00:58:50,640 --> 00:58:52,474
Ahh!

1161
00:59:02,277 --> 00:59:03,861
Well, that's
cutting it close.

1162
00:59:06,072 --> 00:59:08,449
This is why I ask you
to obey me, Sherman.

1163
00:59:09,951 --> 00:59:13,704
Because I'm your father,
and it's my job
to keep you safe.

1164
00:59:14,998 --> 00:59:17,958
But are you sure
Ms. Grunion won't
take me away?

1165
00:59:19,711 --> 00:59:21,587
Not as long
as I'm around.

1166
00:59:33,850 --> 00:59:34,934
 Mr. Peabody!

1167
00:59:35,101 --> 00:59:36,602
Help me!

1168
00:59:37,437 --> 00:59:38,437
Penny!

1169
00:59:45,987 --> 00:59:47,780
Smell my victory!

1170
00:59:47,948 --> 00:59:49,406
Smell it!

1171
00:59:49,574 --> 00:59:51,951
Hey! That's my ride!

1172
00:59:58,875 --> 00:59:59,792
Mr. Peabody...

1173
00:59:59,876 --> 01:00:01,126
hurry!

1174
01:00:04,047 --> 01:00:05,005
I'll take that.

1175
01:00:53,054 --> 01:00:54,722
You did it, Sherman!

1176
01:00:54,889 --> 01:00:55,973
Mr. Peabody helped.

1177
01:00:56,141 --> 01:00:57,683
Now, let's get to
the WABAC, go home,

1178
01:00:57,809 --> 01:00:59,393
un-hypnotize
Penny's parents...

1179
01:00:59,561 --> 01:01:00,769
finish that dinner party,
eat my Baked Alaska...

1180
01:01:00,937 --> 01:01:02,146
charm the pants
off Ms. Grunion...

1181
01:01:02,313 --> 01:01:04,648
and make sure none
of this ever happens
in the first place.

1182
01:01:04,816 --> 01:01:06,608
Sounds good.

1183
01:01:06,776 --> 01:01:07,776
I'm in.

1184
01:01:08,111 --> 01:01:09,278
Ah!

1185
01:01:11,781 --> 01:01:12,573
Sherman!

1186
01:01:13,241 --> 01:01:14,950
 Penny!
Sherman, no!

1187
01:01:25,378 --> 01:01:26,795
Whoa!

1188
01:01:33,720 --> 01:01:35,262
 Mr. Peabody...

1189
01:01:36,097 --> 01:01:37,973
Mr. Peabody?

1190
01:01:39,059 --> 01:01:44,354
Mr. Peabody!

1191
01:01:46,066 --> 01:01:47,357
Dad!

1192
01:01:57,786 --> 01:02:01,747
Oh, Mr. Peabody!
What should I do?
What should I do?

1193
01:02:05,085 --> 01:02:07,461
There's nothing
you can do, Sherman.

1194
01:02:10,548 --> 01:02:12,549
I just want to go home.

1195
01:02:14,761 --> 01:02:15,886
Home. 

1196
01:02:17,138 --> 01:02:18,514
That's it.

1197
01:02:19,015 --> 01:02:20,766
I got an idea.

1198
01:02:21,059 --> 01:02:22,601
Come on!

1199
01:02:24,354 --> 01:02:25,479
Where are we gonna go?

1200
01:02:25,647 --> 01:02:26,814
We're going home.

1201
01:02:26,981 --> 01:02:28,899
There's only one person
who can help us...

1202
01:02:29,067 --> 01:02:30,609
and that's Mr. Peabody.

1203
01:02:30,777 --> 01:02:33,362
What are you talking about?
How is that even possible?

1204
01:02:33,530 --> 01:02:34,780
We've got a time machine,
Penny!

1205
01:02:34,948 --> 01:02:36,740
I can set it so
that we'll get home

1206
01:02:36,866 --> 01:02:38,700
when Mr. Peabody
is still there.

1207
01:02:39,077 --> 01:02:40,327
But I thought
you're not supposed

1208
01:02:40,453 --> 01:02:41,662
to go back to a time
when you existed.

1209
01:02:41,830 --> 01:02:43,330
What choice do we have?

1210
01:02:43,998 --> 01:02:48,460
 Error.
You are attempting to travel
to an era in which you exist.

1211
01:02:48,628 --> 01:02:50,212
This could alter
the fabric of space-time.

1212
01:02:51,881 --> 01:02:54,758
Error. Error.

1213
01:02:55,135 --> 01:02:56,635
Hang on!

1214
01:03:04,477 --> 01:03:05,978
This is fun!

1215
01:03:08,857 --> 01:03:12,151
This is a little
homespun concoction
I like to call...

1216
01:03:12,902 --> 01:03:14,736
"Einstein on the Beach."

1217
01:03:14,904 --> 01:03:16,238
 Yummy.

1218
01:03:18,533 --> 01:03:19,658
To the kids.

1219
01:03:19,826 --> 01:03:21,618
 To the kids!

1220
01:03:22,537 --> 01:03:24,037
 Mr. Peabody.

1221
01:03:24,205 --> 01:03:25,622
Sherman? Penny?

1222
01:03:25,790 --> 01:03:27,124
Can we talk to
you a second?

1223
01:03:27,292 --> 01:03:28,083
Of course.

1224
01:03:28,251 --> 01:03:29,543
Excuse me.

1225
01:03:32,213 --> 01:03:34,131
I've really hit it off
with your parents.

1226
01:03:34,299 --> 01:03:37,467
I think we can file
this night under
"Unqualified Success."

1227
01:03:37,635 --> 01:03:40,053
 I'd hold off
filing it just yet.

1228
01:03:40,221 --> 01:03:41,013
What do you mean?

1229
01:03:41,181 --> 01:03:43,515
Why are you two dressed
like ancient Greeks?

1230
01:03:43,683 --> 01:03:45,184
You used the WABAC!
I did.

1231
01:03:45,351 --> 01:03:46,977
I know, it's terrible!

1232
01:03:47,145 --> 01:03:48,020
But why?

1233
01:03:48,188 --> 01:03:50,230
Penny and I got
into an argument
about George Washington.

1234
01:03:50,398 --> 01:03:51,648
So, I made him
show me the WABAC.

1235
01:03:51,816 --> 01:03:52,983
And I lost her
in ancient Egypt.

1236
01:03:53,109 --> 01:03:54,318
And I got engaged
to King Tut.

1237
01:03:54,485 --> 01:03:56,153
So, I came back
and got you.
Then we ran out of gas.

1238
01:03:56,321 --> 01:03:57,946
In Florence.
Went into a black hole.

1239
01:03:58,114 --> 01:03:59,698
And then you died
in ancient Troy.

1240
01:03:59,866 --> 01:04:02,117
Died? I have a hard
time believing that.

1241
01:04:02,285 --> 01:04:03,118
 It's true!

1242
01:04:03,286 --> 01:04:05,746
But now you're here,
and everything's
gonna be okay.

1243
01:04:05,914 --> 01:04:07,915
I told you never to come back
to a time when you existed...

1244
01:04:08,082 --> 01:04:09,458
because there
would be two of you!

1245
01:04:09,626 --> 01:04:12,085
Yeah, but the other one
of me is in ancient Egypt.

1246
01:04:14,839 --> 01:04:16,965
 Ahh!

1247
01:04:17,091 --> 01:04:18,091
Who are you?

1248
01:04:18,259 --> 01:04:19,927
He's you, but
from another timeline.

1249
01:04:20,094 --> 01:04:23,180
But I thought you said
never to come back to
a time when you existed.

1250
01:04:23,348 --> 01:04:25,015
Exactly!
I know.

1251
01:04:25,767 --> 01:04:29,269
But what was I supposed
to do? Mr. Peabody
died in ancient Troy.

1252
01:04:29,437 --> 01:04:30,187
Died?

1253
01:04:30,355 --> 01:04:31,897
I have a hard time
believing that.

1254
01:04:32,065 --> 01:04:33,023
Thank you.

1255
01:04:33,191 --> 01:04:34,483
What are we going to do?

1256
01:04:34,776 --> 01:04:36,944
Well, for starters,
both Shermans
can't stay here.

1257
01:04:37,111 --> 01:04:38,445
Why? We could
get bunk beds.

1258
01:04:38,613 --> 01:04:39,696
I was thinking
the same thing.

1259
01:04:39,822 --> 01:04:41,448
That's so weird.
It's like we're twins!

1260
01:04:41,532 --> 01:04:42,532
I was thinking that, too!

1261
01:04:42,951 --> 01:04:44,034
 Ow!

1262
01:04:44,118 --> 01:04:46,995
You see? We can't
have two Shermans in
the same timeline.

1263
01:04:47,163 --> 01:04:50,582
It puts too much strain
on the space-time continuum.

1264
01:04:50,750 --> 01:04:52,584
What to do?
The Petersons

1265
01:04:52,669 --> 01:04:54,044
can't know any of this.

1266
01:04:54,212 --> 01:04:55,629
 Hey, Pea-buddy.

1267
01:04:56,339 --> 01:04:57,297
Hey.

1268
01:04:57,465 --> 01:04:58,465
How's it going?

1269
01:04:58,633 --> 01:05:01,218
Patty and I are
working up an appetite.

1270
01:05:01,761 --> 01:05:03,804
Mmm. The smells
coming from your
kitchen are yummy!

1271
01:05:03,972 --> 01:05:06,098
Especially that
Baked Alaska.

1272
01:05:06,683 --> 01:05:08,058
So, what's going on here?

1273
01:05:08,226 --> 01:05:09,559
Yeah, what's
with the getups?

1274
01:05:10,019 --> 01:05:11,436
Toga party!

1275
01:05:11,604 --> 01:05:13,146
 Toga party?

1276
01:05:13,439 --> 01:05:16,817
Yes, it is a toga party!

1277
01:05:16,985 --> 01:05:18,235
 Well, what about dinner?

1278
01:05:18,403 --> 01:05:19,361
I'm starving.

1279
01:05:19,529 --> 01:05:20,696
Why don't we head
into the dining room...

1280
01:05:20,863 --> 01:05:22,781
and tuck into those quails
you've been yakking about?

1281
01:05:22,949 --> 01:05:23,865
No!
Why not?

1282
01:05:24,033 --> 01:05:27,828
Because it's so
fun right here!

1283
01:05:28,162 --> 01:05:30,789
Whoo-hoo! 

1284
01:05:37,922 --> 01:05:38,755
Ms. Grunion!

1285
01:05:38,923 --> 01:05:40,716
How delightful.

1286
01:05:40,800 --> 01:05:42,467
We were having
such a good time...

1287
01:05:42,635 --> 01:05:43,885
I almost forgot
you were coming.
Oh!

1288
01:05:44,053 --> 01:05:45,679
Well, why don't
you join the party?

1289
01:05:45,847 --> 01:05:49,433
I'm not here for a party.
I'm here for
the investigation.

1290
01:05:49,600 --> 01:05:52,853
Good. Why don't
you start investigating
over here?

1291
01:05:53,021 --> 01:05:55,981
Or here, or here,
or here...

1292
01:05:56,149 --> 01:05:57,733
Stop waving your hands around!

1293
01:06:00,695 --> 01:06:01,486
 Sherman?

1294
01:06:01,654 --> 01:06:03,322
Wait! Is that...?

1295
01:06:03,573 --> 01:06:05,115
 Sherman!

1296
01:06:05,283 --> 01:06:08,452
Dos Shermanos? What's
going on here, Peabody?

1297
01:06:08,578 --> 01:06:10,954
Oh...

1298
01:06:11,039 --> 01:06:12,205
Um...

1299
01:06:12,290 --> 01:06:13,457
Nobody move!

1300
01:06:13,624 --> 01:06:16,960
Sherman, I've got to
get you out of here
before you touch yourself.

1301
01:06:18,963 --> 01:06:21,006
Mr. Peabody!
You didn't die!

1302
01:06:21,174 --> 01:06:22,632
Of course I didn't die.

1303
01:06:22,800 --> 01:06:23,884
Thank you.

1304
01:06:24,093 --> 01:06:25,969
Hey. How did you get back?

1305
01:06:26,137 --> 01:06:27,763
Well, after a few
failed experiments...

1306
01:06:27,930 --> 01:06:30,140
I hit upon a combination
of bones, stone
and yak fat...

1307
01:06:30,308 --> 01:06:32,309
and constructed
a rudimentary WABAC.

1308
01:06:32,477 --> 01:06:33,435
You know what they say...

1309
01:06:33,603 --> 01:06:36,813
"If at first
you don't succeed,
Troy, Troy again."

1310
01:06:36,981 --> 01:06:39,649
This is no time for puns!
Even good ones.

1311
01:06:39,817 --> 01:06:41,276
Penny, Sherman,
quickly!

1312
01:06:41,527 --> 01:06:43,320
You're not going anywhere.

1313
